{"title_page": "Outlook Media", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file      = Outlook Media Kit Cover.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = ''Outlook Media'' media kit and image used for ''Outlook Columbus'' May 2009 Urban Living Issue\n| editor         = Christopher L. Hayes\n| editor_title   = President & Publisher\n| editor2          = Robert B. Vitale\n| editor_title2    = Editor-in-chief\n| editor3         = Chad P. Frye\n| editor_title3   = Publisher and Director of Revenue\n| frequency       = Monthly\n| circulation     = 25,000 per issue\n| category        = [[Newsmagazine]]\n| company         = Outlook Media\n| publisher       = Chad P. Frye, Chris L. Hayes, Robert B. Vitale\n| founded       = 1995\n| finaldate       = 2017\n| finalnumber     = \n| country         = USA\n| based           = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{url|http://www.outlookcolumbus.com/}}\n| issn            = 4702-5131 \n}}\n'''Outlook Media''' was a [[Columbus, Ohio]]-based [[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[bisexual]], [[transgender]] ([[LGBT]]) lifestyle and advocacy company for the Ohio [[queer]] and allied community from 1995 until late 2017. Their flagship product, ''Outlook Columbus'' was a news, politics, and lifestyle magazine. Outlook Media also published ''High Street Neighborhoods'', managed Columbus' LGBT and allied business networking group, Network Columbus, and partnered with the [[Ohio Historical Society]] to form the Gay Ohio History Initiative.  In 2015, Outlook Media began to publish The Love Big LGBT Wedding Expo Guide, and began holding Love Big LGBT Wedding Expos throughout [[Ohio]].\n\n==Publications and Community Initiatives==\n===Outlook Columbus===\n''[[Outlook Columbus]]'' was a monthly, glossy lifestyle and advocacy magazine geared toward Ohio's LGBT and [[urban area|urban]] progressive communities. [[Editorial]] coverage includes politics, small businesses, arts & entertainment, health & wellness, faith, fashion, sports, interviews, horoscopes, events and community news. With content that contains both locally and nationally focused features.<ref name=\"outlookmedia1\">[http://www.outlookmedia.com/ Outlook media.] Retrieved 7-20-10</ref>  The publication replaced ''Outlook Weekly'' as the company's primary publication. With over 25,000 print copies distributed monthly, the magazine can be found for free in over 3,000 locations throughout Ohio, including local libraries, restaurants, and night clubs or by paid, home-delivery subscription. ''Outlook Columbus'' differentiates itself from similar LGBT publications by its advertising. ''[[Outlook Columbus|Outlook]]'' doesn't limit its partners to gay-owned or gay-themed advertisers but also gay-friendly or straight owned but open-minded type businesses including national advertisers [[Bank One]], [[Time Warner]], and [[American Express]] among local businesses.<ref>Wilder, Brent. 5-27-05. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/othercities/dayton/stories/2005/05/30/smallb1.html Reaching outside the circle]. [[Business First#Newspapers|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved 7-20-10.</ref> The magazine's content is diverse as well, targeting a large cross section of the community while at the same time speaking to specific groups under the large LGBT umbrella.<ref name=\"outlookmedia1\"/> According to studies listed on their corporate website, ''Outlook Columbus'' is the number one media choice for the [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] LGBT and allied community, the number one media choice for newcomers to Columbus who have been in the city for 5 years or less, and the number two print choice for [[African Americans]] in Columbus.<ref name=\"outlookmedia1\"/>\n\nOutlookohio.com was the magazine's online counterpart.  Boasting 100 times the content of the print publication, the website keeps readers engaged all month long with fresh daily content, news, event photos, contests, polls, videos and reader comments.\n\nIn 2015, [[Outlook Columbus|Outlook]] celebrated 20 years of publishing.\n\nIn June 2017, [[Outlook Columbus|Outlook]] ceased publication.\n\n=== Love Big LGBT Wedding Expos ===\nOhio's only LGBT and allied wedding expo series, Love Big Expos offer a safe and welcoming place for LGBT couples to meet vendors who are committed to [[marriage equality]] and excited to serve the LGBT community. Love Big relieves the added stress of coming out to potentially non-supportive vendors by putting equality-minded businesses all in one place. Because Ohio still does not legally recognize marriage equality, LGBT couples have to go out of state to get their licensing. However, more and more Ohio LGBT couples are choosing to hold their big religious ceremonies and receptions in the state.\n\nEvents are free and open to the public. Straight couples are welcome, too.\n\n=== ''Love Big LGBT Wedding Guide'' ===\n[[Ohio|Ohio's]] first print and digital LGBT wedding guide & directory, Love Big Wedding Guide is a free, full color, perfect bound 9\u2033 x 10.875\u2033, premium paper stock magazine featuring equality-minded vendors servicing the [[Ohio]] market. The [[advertorial]]-focused guidebook is complemented by original industry focused content. Over 50,000 copies will be distributed statewide annually to wedding vendors, shops, universities, restaurants, coffee houses, libraries, community centers and subscribers.\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file      = High Street Neighborhoods April-Aug 2008 Cover.png\n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = Chris Hayes\n| editor_title    = \n| previous_editor = Aaron Leventhal\n| staff_writer    = \n| editor2         = Chad P. Frye\n| editor_title2   = Advertising director\n| frequency       = Bi-Annual\n| circulation     = 75,000 per issue\n| category        = Saver Magazine\n| company         = Outlook Media\n| publisher       =\n| founded       = 2000\n| country         = USA\n| based           = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{url|http://livelocalcolumbus.com/}}\n| issn            = \n}}\n\n===High Street Neighborhoods===\n\n''High Street Neighborhoods'' is a bi-annual, community based saver-magazine whose audience is the general public that resides within the [[Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area|Columbus]] urban core. Each issue is divided into community based sections where local advertisers present coupons. These communities include [[Merion Village]], [[German Village]], the [[Brewery District]], [[Downtown Columbus, Ohio|Downtown]], the King Lincoln District, the [[Arena District]], the [[Short North]] Arts District, the [[Ohio State University|University District]], [[Clintonville, Ohio|Clintonville]], [[Worthington, Ohio|Worthington]], [[Grandview Heights, Ohio|Grandview]], [[Franklinton, Columbus, Ohio|Franklinton]], and Old Town East. Features also include a travel guide, service directory, and pet directory. The publication is distributed to more than 200 Columbus locations where it can be found for free including recreation centers, Columbus [[YMCA]], and [http://experiencecolumbus.com/ Experience Columbus] visitors centers.<ref>[http://highstreetmoneysavers.com/ High Street Money Savers.] Retrieved July 20, 2010 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917132230/http://highstreetmoneysavers.com/ |date=September 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Network Columbus===\n''Network Columbus'' has been dubbed Central Ohio's 'gay chamber of commerce.' <ref>Wilder, Brent. May 27, 2005. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/othercities/dayton/stories/2005/05/30/smallb1.html Reaching outside the circle]. [[Business First#Newspapers|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref> The organization, with 3000 members, provides networking events, educational programs, business advocacy and linkages with other business and professional organizations with the purpose to lead and support economic growth within the central Ohio LGBT community.<ref>[http://www.networkcolumbus.com/ Network Columbus]. Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref>\n\n===Gay Ohio History Initiative===\n''Outlook Media'' and [[Ohio Historical Society|''The Ohio Historical Society'']] created this initiative to include memorabilia and memories for gays across the state.<ref>Williams, Sherri. October 17, 2005. Historical society to document gays' past. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref> As of summer 2010, two exhibits, Remembering the Berwick Ball, and The International Drag King Community Extravaganza Exhibit, have been curated by the Gay Ohio History initiative. A traveling exhibit is in the works.<ref>[http://www.gohi.org/ Gay Ohio History Initiative]. Retrieved June 20, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Past Publications and Initiatives==\n===Radio Outlook===\n''Radio Outlook'' is a weekly GLBT talk-radio show and the first of its kind in Ohio. Hosted by Chris Hayes and Chad Frye, the show has a leftward lean, targeting the GLBT community but is enjoyed by a larger audience who enjoyed current events and friendly, informed banter.<ref>Fisher, Ann. September 26, 2008. Gay talk show speaks to broad audience. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch]]. Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref>\n\n===TV Outlook===\n''TV Outlook'' is similar in format to ''Radio Outlook''. It was available on [[WDEM-CD]].\n\n===Outlook===\n''Outlook'' was the company's first publication. It was a bi-weekly newspaper and followed a newspaper approach in layout based in strong journalism and professional design, rather than serving as a promotional publication for the [[Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area|Greater Columbus]] LGBT community. Circulation was between 8,000 and 12,000 and distributed to over 200 locations.\n\n===Outlook Weekly===\n''Outlook Weekly'' replaced ''Outlook'' as the companies primary publication. Published every week rather than every other week, the newspaper had similar content and format. In 2004, the publication switched content slightly, from just a [[News|news tabloid]] to a [[lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle tabloid]] as well.\n\n==History==\nOutlook Publishing, Inc. was founded by co-owners and publishers Jeffrey D. Cox and Jim Ryan in the spring of 1995 with the primary purpose of publishing their paper titled ''Outlook''. Ryan was editor and managed distribution while Cox managed finances, layout, and design from his home. The paper relied on volunteer initiative and freelance reporters to operate. Before ''Outlook'''s establishment, the only other GLBT focused publications in Ohio were the ''[[Gay People's Chronicle]]'', which was based out of [[Cleveland]], and a monthly publication from [[Stonewall Columbus]]. ''Outlook'' was created to fill the void as a news voice for the Columbus community.\n\nUnder Cox, and Ryan's ownership, the newspaper quickly became respected as a professional news source. In the fall of 1998, ''Outlook'' earned five writing awards, called the [[Vice Versa (magazine)|Vice Versa Awards for Excellence]] in the Gay and Lesbian Press, from the [[National Gay and Lesbian Journalists Association]] and received third place for Best Newspaper in the weekly or bi-weekly category. These awards were given for the paper's approach to controversial topics and the effect they had on the Columbus community. For example, when ''Outlook'' published a piece about anti-gay harassment by members of the [[Ohio State University]] wrestling team, the OSU Athletic Department created mandatory sexual orientation cultural competence training for all its employees.\n\nIn early 1999, Outlook Publishing, Inc. was sold to Lynn Greer, Jose Rodriguez, and Malcolm Riggle operating from Riggle's offices in [[Worthington, Ohio]]. Within the year Rodriguez sold his share of the company to Greer and Riggle.\n\nIn the fall of 2003, Malcom Riggle assumed sole-ownership of company operations. Under his leadership, ''Outlook Weekly'' became a lifestyle tabloid. That November, Outlook Publishing, Inc. changed names to Outlook Media, Inc. Two years later, in the fall of 2005, Outlook teamed with the [[Ohio Historical Society]] to form the ''Gay Ohio History Initiative''.<ref>Williams, Sherri. 10-17-05. Historical society to document gays' past. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> Also within the year, the magazine saw controversy in a surrounding [[Columbus, Ohio]] suburb. Some members of the [[Upper Arlington, Ohio|Upper Arlington]] community tried to ban the newspaper from its libraries, but after library board discussions the paper was decided to remain available to patrons.<ref>Narciso, Dean. August 31, 2005. Library Will Keep 2 Gay Papers. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch.]] Retrieved 7-20-10.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Outlook Media changed ownership after seven years under Malcom Riggle. Chris Hayes and Michael Daniels bought the company and moved Outlook's offices to [[The Short North]].<ref>[http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2006/06/19/daily28.html Outlook Weekly publisher sold]. ''Columbus Business First''. Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> Under their leadership, ''Outlook Weekly'''s audience expanded to the Columbus progressive community while still maintaining its readership base in the GLBT community.<ref name=\"bizjournals1\">Kemper, Kevin. August 12, 2010. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2008/09/15/story8.html Outlook Weekly expands reach]. [[Business First#Newspapers|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref> In the summer of 2008, Outlook Media started its radio program, ''Radio Outlook'' which lasted one year.<ref name=\"bizjournals1\"/>\n\n''Outlook Weekly'' changed format to a monthly magazine in 2009, changing names to ''Outlook Columbus''. The final issue of ''Outlook Weekly'' was released on March 25, 2009.<ref>[http://www.columbusunderground.com/outlook-weekly-goes-outlook-monthly Outlook Weekly Goes Outlook Monthly]. ''Columbus Underground'' Retrieved March 19, 2009. July 20, 2010.</ref> The monthly format changed the look of the publication by upgrading to paper stock and including more in-depth features while still remaining free to the public.<ref>Burns, Matt. April 18, 2010. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2009/03/16/daily25.html Outlook weekly going monthly]. [[Business First|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> ''Outlook Columbus'' has had successful pieces including an article interview with [[Ohio State University|Ohio State]] football coach [[Jim Tressel]] that reached national acclaim. The piece was reprinted on March 3, 2010 in ''Outsports'', which caters to the gay sports community.<ref>Daniels, Michael. March 3, 2010. [http://www.outsports.com/os/index.php/component/content/article/57-interviews/302-jim-tressel-everybody-is-important Jim Tressel: 'Everybody is important']. ''Out Sports'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> From here, news of the article reached [[ESPN]], where it was reprinted again on March 4.<ref>Rittenberg, Adam. March 4, 2010. [http://espn.go.com/blog/bigten/post/_/id/10619/osus-tressel-talks-acceptance-with-glbt-publication OSU's Tressel talks acceptance with GLBT.] ''[[ESPN College Football]].'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' then picked up the story and positively commented on the Tressel interview on March 8, 2010. After the ''Sports Illustrated'' article, the story went viral across the country including reports by the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' <ref>Knapp, Gwen. March 11, 2010. [http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-03-11/sports/18385043_1_gay-athletes-same-sex-nuptials-gay-friendly-city Closet door opens just a bit]. ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]].'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> and ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'''s '150 Reasons to Have Pride' among others.<ref>June\u2013July 2010. [http://www.advocate.com/Article.aspx?id=110662 150 Reasons to Have Pride in 2010.] ''The Advocate.'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn July 2013 Chad Frye and Bob Vitale of the Columbus Dispatch joined Christopher Hayes as Co-Publishers. The additional partners created capacity to re-launch the publication across the entire state of Ohio, with major distribution hubs in Cincinnati, Cleveland, Columbus, Toledo, Dayton, Youngstown, Canton, and Akron. \n \nIn June 2016, Co-publishers Chad Frye and Robert Vitale exited the company, leaving Christopher Hayes as sole owner and publisher.\n\nIn July 2017 Outlook ceased publication, and the assets of the company were liquidated.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.outlookmedia.com/}}\n\n{{LGBT}}\n\n[[Category:American LGBT-related magazines]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Media in Columbus, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file      = Outlook Media Kit Cover.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = ''Outlook Media'' media kit and image used for ''Outlook Columbus'' May 2009 Urban Living Issue\n| editor         = Christopher L. Hayes\n| editor_title   = President & Publisher\n| editor2          = Robert B. Vitale\n| editor_title2    = Editor-in-chief\n| editor3         = Chad P. Frye\n| editor_title3   = Publisher and Director of Revenue\n| frequency       = Monthly\n| circulation     = 25,000 per issue\n| category        = [[Newsmagazine]]\n| company         = Outlook Media\n| publisher       = Chad P. Frye, Chris L. Hayes, Robert B. Vitale\n| founded       = 1995\n| finaldate       = 2017\n| finalnumber     = \n| country         = USA\n| based           = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{url|http://www.outlookcolumbus.com/}}\n| issn            = 4702-5131 \n}}\n'''Outlook Media''' was a [[Columbus, Ohio]]-based [[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[bisexual]], [[transgender]] ([[LGBT]]) lifestyle and advocacy company for the Ohio [[queer]] and allied community from 1995 until late 2017. Their flagship product, ''Outlook Columbus'' was a news, politics, and lifestyle magazine. Outlook Media also published ''High Street Neighborhoods'', managed Columbus' LGBT and allied business networking group, Network Columbus, and partnered with the [[Ohio Historical Society]] to form the Gay Ohio History Initiative.  In 2015, Outlook Media began to publish The Love Big LGBT Wedding Expo Guide, and began holding Love Big LGBT Wedding Expos throughout [[Ohio]].\n\n==Publications and Community Initiatives==\n===Outlook Columbus===\n''[[Outlook Columbus]]'' was a monthly, glossy lifestyle and advocacy magazine geared toward Ohio's LGBT and [[urban area|urban]] progressive communities. [[Editorial]] coverage includes politics, small businesses, arts & entertainment, health & wellness, faith, fashion, sports, interviews, horoscopes, events and community news. With content that contains both locally and nationally focused features.<ref name=\"outlookmedia1\">[http://www.outlookmedia.com/ Outlook media.] Retrieved 7-20-10</ref>  The publication replaced ''Outlook Weekly'' as the company's primary publication. With over 25,000 print copies distributed monthly, the magazine can be found for free in over 3,000 locations throughout Ohio, including local libraries, restaurants, and night clubs or by paid, home-delivery subscription. ''Outlook Columbus'' differentiates itself from similar LGBT publications by its advertising. ''[[Outlook Columbus|Outlook]]'' doesn't limit its partners to gay-owned or gay-themed advertisers but also gay-friendly or straight owned but open-minded type businesses including national advertisers [[Bank One]], [[Time Warner]], and [[American Express]] among local businesses.<ref>Wilder, Brent. 5-27-05. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/othercities/dayton/stories/2005/05/30/smallb1.html Reaching outside the circle]. [[Business First#Newspapers|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved 7-20-10.</ref> The magazine's content is diverse as well, targeting a large cross section of the community while at the same time speaking to specific groups under the large LGBT umbrella.<ref name=\"outlookmedia1\"/> According to studies listed on their corporate website, ''Outlook Columbus'' is the number one media choice for the [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] LGBT and allied community, the number one media choice for newcomers to Columbus who have been in the city for 5 years or less, and the number two print choice for [[African Americans]] in Columbus.<ref name=\"outlookmedia1\"/>\n\nOutlookohio.com was the magazine's online counterpart.  Boasting 100 times the content of the print publication, the website keeps readers engaged all month long with fresh daily content, news, event photos, contests, polls, videos and reader comments.\n\nIn 2015, [[Outlook Columbus|Outlook]] celebrated 20 years of publishing.\n\nIn June 2017, [[Outlook Columbus|Outlook]] ceased publication.\n\n=== Love Big LGBT Wedding Expos ===\nOhio's only LGBT and allied wedding expo series, Love Big Expos offer a safe and welcoming place for LGBT couples to meet vendors who are committed to [[marriage equality]] and excited to serve the LGBT community. Love Big relieves the added stress of coming out to potentially non-supportive vendors by putting equality-minded businesses all in one place. Because Ohio still does not legally recognize marriage equality, LGBT couples have to go out of state to get their licensing. However, more and more Ohio LGBT couples are choosing to hold their big religious ceremonies and receptions in the state.\n\nEvents are free and open to the public. Straight couples are welcome, too.\n\n=== ''Love Big LGBT Wedding Guide'' ===\n[[Ohio|Ohio's]] first print and digital LGBT wedding guide & directory, Love Big Wedding Guide is a free, full color, perfect bound 9\u2033 x 10.875\u2033, premium paper stock magazine featuring equality-minded vendors servicing the [[Ohio]] market. The [[advertorial]]-focused guidebook is complemented by original industry focused content. Over 50,000 copies will be distributed statewide annually to wedding vendors, shops, universities, restaurants, coffee houses, libraries, community centers and subscribers.\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| image_file      = High Street Neighborhoods April-Aug 2008 Cover.png\n| image_size      = \n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = Chris Hayes\n| editor_title    = \n| previous_editor = Aaron Leventhal\n| staff_writer    = \n| editor2         = Chad P. Frye\n| editor_title2   = Advertising director\n| frequency       = Bi-Annual\n| circulation     = 75,000 per issue\n| category        = Saver Magazine\n| company         = Outlook Media\n| publisher       =\n| founded       = 2000\n| country         = USA\n| based           = [[Columbus, Ohio]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{url|http://livelocalcolumbus.com/}}\n| issn            = \n}}\n\n===High Street Neighborhoods===\n\n''High Street Neighborhoods'' is a bi-annual, community based saver-magazine whose audience is the general public that resides within the [[Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area|Columbus]] urban core. Each issue is divided into community based sections where local advertisers present coupons. These communities include [[Merion Village]], [[German Village]], the [[Brewery District]], [[Downtown Columbus, Ohio|Downtown]], the King Lincoln District, the [[Arena District]], the [[Short North]] Arts District, the [[Ohio State University|University District]], [[Clintonville, Ohio|Clintonville]], [[Worthington, Ohio|Worthington]], [[Grandview Heights, Ohio|Grandview]], [[Franklinton, Columbus, Ohio|Franklinton]], and Old Town East. Features also include a travel guide, service directory, and pet directory. The publication is distributed to more than 200 Columbus locations where it can be found for free including recreation centers, Columbus [[YMCA]], and [http://experiencecolumbus.com/ Experience Columbus] visitors centers.<ref>[http://highstreetmoneysavers.com/ High Street Money Savers.] Retrieved July 20, 2010 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917132230/http://highstreetmoneysavers.com/ |date=September 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Network Columbus===\n''Network Columbus'' has been dubbed Central Ohio's 'gay chamber of commerce.' <ref>Wilder, Brent. May 27, 2005. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/othercities/dayton/stories/2005/05/30/smallb1.html Reaching outside the circle]. [[Business First#Newspapers|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref> The organization, with 3000 members, provides networking events, educational programs, business advocacy and linkages with other business and professional organizations with the purpose to lead and support economic growth within the central Ohio LGBT community.<ref>[http://www.networkcolumbus.com/ Network Columbus]. Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref>\n\n===Gay Ohio History Initiative===\n''Outlook Media'' and [[Ohio Historical Society|''The Ohio Historical Society'']] created this initiative to include memorabilia and memories for gays across the state.<ref>Williams, Sherri. October 17, 2005. Historical society to document gays' past. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref> As of summer 2010, two exhibits, Remembering the Berwick Ball, and The International Drag King Community Extravaganza Exhibit, have been curated by the Gay Ohio History initiative. A traveling exhibit is in the works.<ref>[http://www.gohi.org/ Gay Ohio History Initiative]. Retrieved June 20, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Past Publications and Initiatives==\n===Radio Outlook===\n''Radio Outlook'' is a weekly GLBT talk-radio show and the first of its kind in Ohio. Hosted by Chris Hayes and Chad Frye, the show has a leftward lean, targeting the GLBT community but is enjoyed by a larger audience who enjoyed current events and friendly, informed banter.<ref>Fisher, Ann. September 26, 2008. Gay talk show speaks to broad audience. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch]]. Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref>\n\n===TV Outlook===\n''TV Outlook'' is similar in format to ''Radio Outlook''. It was available on [[WDEM-CD]].\n\n===Outlook===\n''Outlook'' was the company's first publication. It was a bi-weekly newspaper and followed a newspaper approach in layout based in strong journalism and professional design, rather than serving as a promotional publication for the [[Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area|Greater Columbus]] LGBT community. Circulation was between 8,000 and 12,000 and distributed to over 200 locations.\n\n===Outlook Weekly===\n''Outlook Weekly'' replaced ''Outlook'' as the companies primary publication. Published every week rather than every other week, the newspaper had similar content and format. In 2004, the publication switched content slightly, from just a [[News|news tabloid]] to a [[lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle tabloid]] as well.\n\n==History==\nOutlook Publishing, Inc. was founded by co-owners and publishers Jeffrey D. Cox and Jim Ryan in the spring of 1995 with the primary purpose of publishing their paper titled ''Outlook''. Ryan was editor and managed distribution while Cox managed finances, layout, and design from his home. The paper relied on volunteer initiative and freelance reporters to operate. Before ''Outlook'''s establishment, the only other GLBT focused publications in Ohio were the ''[[Gay People's Chronicle]]'', which was based out of [[Cleveland]], and a monthly publication from [[Stonewall Columbus]]. ''Outlook'' was created to fill the void as a news voice for the Columbus community.\n\nUnder Cox, and Ryan's ownership, the newspaper quickly became respected as a professional news source. In the fall of 1998, ''Outlook'' earned five writing awards, called the [[Vice Versa (magazine)|Vice Versa Awards for Excellence]] in the Gay and Lesbian Press, from the [[National Gay and Lesbian Journalists Association]] and received third place for Best Newspaper in the weekly or bi-weekly category. These awards were given for the paper's approach to controversial topics and the effect they had on the Columbus community. For example, when ''Outlook'' published a piece about anti-gay harassment by members of the [[Ohio State University]] wrestling team, the OSU Athletic Department created mandatory sexual orientation cultural competence training for all its employees.\n\nIn early 1999, Outlook Publishing, Inc. was sold to Lynn Greer, Jose Rodriguez, and Malcolm Riggle operating from Riggle's offices in [[Worthington, Ohio]]. Within the year Rodriguez sold his share of the company to Greer and Riggle.\n\nIn the fall of 2003, Malcom Riggle assumed sole-ownership of company operations. Under his leadership, ''Outlook Weekly'' became a lifestyle tabloid. That November, Outlook Publishing, Inc. changed names to Outlook Media, Inc. Two years later, in the fall of 2005, Outlook teamed with the [[Ohio Historical Society]] to form the ''Gay Ohio History Initiative''.<ref>Williams, Sherri. 10-17-05. Historical society to document gays' past. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> Also within the year, the magazine saw controversy in a surrounding [[Columbus, Ohio]] suburb. Some members of the [[Upper Arlington, Ohio|Upper Arlington]] community tried to ban the newspaper from its libraries, but after library board discussions the paper was decided to remain available to patrons.<ref>Narciso, Dean. August 31, 2005. Library Will Keep 2 Gay Papers. [[Columbus Dispatch|The Columbus Dispatch.]] Retrieved 7-20-10.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Outlook Media changed ownership after seven years under Malcom Riggle. Chris Hayes and Michael Daniels bought the company and moved Outlook's offices to [[The Short North]].<ref>[http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2006/06/19/daily28.html Outlook Weekly publisher sold]. ''Columbus Business First''. Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> Under their leadership, ''Outlook Weekly'''s audience expanded to the Columbus progressive community while still maintaining its readership base in the GLBT community.<ref name=\"bizjournals1\">Kemper, Kevin. August 12, 2010. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2008/09/15/story8.html Outlook Weekly expands reach]. [[Business First#Newspapers|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010</ref> In the summer of 2008, Outlook Media started its radio program, ''Radio Outlook'' which lasted one year.<ref name=\"bizjournals1\"/>\n\n''Outlook Weekly'' changed format to a monthly magazine in 2009, changing names to ''Outlook Columbus''. The final issue of ''Outlook Weekly'' was released on March 25, 2009.<ref>[http://www.columbusunderground.com/outlook-weekly-goes-outlook-monthly Outlook Weekly Goes Outlook Monthly]. ''Columbus Underground'' Retrieved March 19, 2009. July 20, 2010.</ref> The monthly format changed the look of the publication by upgrading to paper stock and including more in-depth features while still remaining free to the public.<ref>Burns, Matt. April 18, 2010. [http://columbus.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2009/03/16/daily25.html Outlook weekly going monthly]. [[Business First|''Columbus Business First''.]] Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> ''Outlook Columbus'' has had successful pieces including an article interview with [[Ohio State University|Ohio State]] football coach [[Jim Tressel]] that reached national acclaim. The piece was reprinted on March 3, 2010 in ''Outsports'', which caters to the gay sports community.<ref>Daniels, Michael. March 3, 2010. [http://www.outsports.com/os/index.php/component/content/article/57-interviews/302-jim-tressel-everybody-is-important Jim Tressel: 'Everybody is important']. ''Out Sports'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> From here, news of the article reached [[ESPN]], where it was reprinted again on March 4.<ref>Rittenberg, Adam. March 4, 2010. [http://espn.go.com/blog/bigten/post/_/id/10619/osus-tressel-talks-acceptance-with-glbt-publication OSU's Tressel talks acceptance with GLBT.] ''[[ESPN College Football]].'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' then picked up the story and positively commented on the Tressel interview on March 8, 2010. After the ''Sports Illustrated'' article, the story went viral across the country including reports by the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' <ref>Knapp, Gwen. March 11, 2010. [http://articles.sfgate.com/2010-03-11/sports/18385043_1_gay-athletes-same-sex-nuptials-gay-friendly-city Closet door opens just a bit]. ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]].'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref> and ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'''s '150 Reasons to Have Pride' among others.<ref>June\u2013July 2010. [http://www.advocate.com/Article.aspx?id=110662 150 Reasons to Have Pride in 2010.] ''The Advocate.'' Retrieved July 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn July 2013 Chad Frye and Bob Vitale of the Columbus Dispatch joined Christopher Hayes as Co-Publishers. The additional partners created capacity to re-launch the publication across the entire state of Ohio, with major distribution hubs in Cincinnati, Cleveland, Columbus, Toledo, Dayton, Youngstown, Canton, and Akron. \n \nIn June 2016, Co-publishers Chad Frye and Robert Vitale exited the company, leaving Christopher Hayes as sole owner and publisher.\n\nIn July 2017 Outlook ceased publication, and the assets of the company were liquidated.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.outlookmedia.com/}}\n\n{{LGBT}}\n\n[[Category:American LGBT-related magazines]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines|Outlook Columbus]]\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Cultural magazines|Outlook Columbus]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Media in Columbus, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlook_Media"}
{"title_page": "D'Arcy Jones", "text_new": "{{Infobox architect\n| name = D'Arcy Jones\n| practice = D'Arcy Jones Architects\n| significant_buildings = \n| significant_projects = \n| website = https://www.darcyjones.com/\n| birth_place = Fort St.John, British Columbia\n| education = University of Manitoba\n}}\n\nD\u2019Arcy Jones is a Canadian [[architect]] and the founding principle of [https://www.darcyjones.com/ D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects] (DJA) (formerly known as D\u2019Arcy Jones Architecture), a studio practice based out of [[Vancouver|Vancouver British Columbia, Canada]]. DJA\u2019s portfolio consists of completed and ongoing projects focusing greatly within their local area of British Columbia while some reside as far as Ontario, Washington, California, and Switzerland.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reminetwork.com/articles/emerging-talent-of-architect-darcy-jones/|title=The emerging talent of architect D'Arcy Jones - REMI Network|website=REMINET|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/raic-awards-excellence-emerging-architectural-practice-award/|title=RAIC Awards of Excellence: Emerging Architectural Practice Award|date=2017-05-12|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects focuses mainly on small scale boutique residential homes, many of which have brought national and international recognition for the practice.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://raic.org/awards/emerging-architectural-practice-award-%E2%80%94-2017-recipient|website=raic.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects in tandem with Jones himself has award-winning work that has been widely published in magazines, newspapers, books, journals and interviews. His emerging recognition has gained him respect from awards won through his adaptive reuse approach on existing Vancouver houses.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Canadian Modern Architecture|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|year=2019|isbn=9781616896454|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> The practice and specific projects have received many awards highlighting things like design excellence and emerging firm recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aibc.memberpro.net/main/body.cfm?menu=directory&submenu=directoryBusiness&page_no=108&records_perpage_qy=1&city_nm=&company_nm=d&mode=search&searchField=company_nm&search_value=d&record_id=108&table_id=2381&total_pages=53&total_records=523&more_pages=42&more_records=413|title=Architectural Institute of BC|website=aibc.memberpro.net|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/darcy-jones-wins-ronald-j-thom-award-for-early-design-achievement/|title=D'Arcy Jones wins Ronald J. Thom Award for Early Design Achievement|date=2014-07-22|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.dal.ca/news/alumni/big-win-for-darcy-jones-architecture/|title=Big win for Vancouver-based company D\u2019Arcy Jones Architecture (DJA)|date=2017-06-01|website=Dalhousie Alumni|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Jones himself is an architect registration in the provinces of in BC ([[Architectural Institute of British Columbia|AIBC]]), Manitoba ([https://www.mbarchitects.org/ MAA]), Ontario ([[Ontario Association of Architects|OAA]]) and a member of the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada]] (MRAIC). <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/copy-of-people|title=People|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\n== Early Life and Career ==\nD\u2019arcy Jones is a Canadian native, born and raised in British Columbia. Although born in [[Fort St. John, British Columbia|Fort St. John]] Jones spent his early life growing up in [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]]. From early on, Jones developed both an artistic interest in drawing and the physical act of building. Jones\u2019 interest in physical design continued to grow during highschool grade 11 when he was enrolled in a class that taught drafting.<ref name=\":1\" /> This eventually drove him to pursue post secondary to achieve both a bachelors and a masters degree. In 1995, Jones received a bachelor's degree in Environmental Design at the [[University of Manitoba]] followed by a bachelor of Environmental Design Studies at the [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] (TUNS)(which merged into what is now [[Dalhousie University]]) in 1997.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Shortly after, he returned back to the University of Manitoba where he completed his masters in Architecture in 1999.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nDuring his time still as an undergrad student in university, Jones was already designing architecture that made its way into physical realization. His first real project was a commission done in 1996 by his own parents asking him to design their home.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/features/article/150068361/vancouver-based-d-arcy-jones-architecture-stays-small-to-maintain-intimacy-with-their-work|title=Vancouver Based D'Arcy Jones Architecture Stays Small to Maintain Intimacy With Their Work|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> During this time, Jones claims that the project made him appreciate and \u201cfall in love\u201d with factors that were not taught in architecture school, such as the practical and technical characteristics of architecture.<ref name=\":5\" /> The success of this solo project caused him to find his own practice after graduating from masters in 1999, where he would officially start practicing alone from the years 2000-2005.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> During these early times as a solo practice, Jones was based out of his personal house located in Vancouver\u2019s west end.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nProfessionally, Jones followed a path that was considered abnormal and non-traditional. As typically seen in Canada (where he would eventually practice) and many other parts of the world, the licensing process remains very strict and orderly in terms of how to achieve official registration as a practicing architect. With respect to contemporary licensing, the process follows a structure where an individual with a Masters of Architecture degree will work under the title of \u2018[[Intern architect|intern]]\u2019 through already established firms. Instead, Jones founded his own practice,\u00a0right after graduating in 1999 and has been self-employed ever since.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Unlike in a normal intern employment situation where a registered architect will supervise and sign off on one\u2019s \u2018working hours,\u2019 Jones never traditionally interned and obtained his hours remaining as a solo practice by collaborations and joint ventures. He states in an interview that he used joint ventures with registered architects as a means to carry out projects and complete his \u2018internship.\u2019<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAfter 5 years of solo practice, Jones moved the practice from his own home into an office space in Mount Pleasant in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" /> From here Jones officially founded D\u2019Arcy Jones Architecture (currently known as D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects) where he expanded his studio size to a humble 9 person team including himself.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Although technically involved with architectural practice since the conception of his firm in 2000, Jones achieved being a registered architect in 2013.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAs an established architect and practice, Jones actively involves himself and contributes within the field of architecture through talk panels, design competitions, lecturing, juries, and teaching. In 2015, Jones was taken on by the University of British Columbia to be an adjunct professor within their schools of Architecture and Landscape Architecture where things like studio teaching, critiquing and being a thesis advisor are carried out.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Most recently, he was invited by the [[University of Calgary]] as a guest critic for students\u2019 within the Faculty of Environmental Design.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Design Approach ==\nD\u2019Arcy Jones has always been recognized for his boutique residential houses ever since completing his very first project as a student. To this day, Jones has gained respect through his most notable works and completed projects which fall largely under the typology of single residential housing.<ref name=\":6\" /> Alongside the natural evolution of the firm, projects encompassing a broader typology but keeping in similar scale include galleries, renovations, interiors, commercial and gallery spaces.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nJones\u2019 projects focus greatly on the exploration and combination of program together with proportion, and how site and materiality shape it. Furthermore, these aspects help DJA explore the technicalities of details and construction as integral parts of the design process.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nJones has always been a proponent of the deeper characteristics of sustainability and inherently is seen translated into DJA\u2019s project designs and philosophies.<ref name=\":5\" /> As seen through Vancouver's First Shaughnessy Design Panel, Jones was actively involved representing the [[Architectural Institute of British Columbia]] ([[Architectural Institute of British Columbia|AIBC]]). This was a panel that fundamentally helped establish Vancouver\u2019s prohibition against demolishing heritage houses that dated before the 1940\u2019s.<ref name=\":0\" /> From a design perspective, DJA\u2019s philosophy encourages the integration of modern expression by using existing buildings as a starting point or blank canvas.<ref name=\":1\" /> In many of DJA\u2019s projects, intensive renovations and adaptive reuse of existing homes seems to be where opportunities in showcasing sustainability take place through innovation and thoughtful recycling.<ref name=\":2\" /> As stated by Jones, \"the greenest building is the one already built,\" and this further encourages their projects to address material efficiently and re imagine innovative sustainable designs to introduce things like passive cooling and breezes to save energy.<ref name=\":5\" /> Through their designs, Jones\u2019 also encourages design sustainability through key factors like favoring common and local building materials over nonnative and foreign ones.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> This ultimately challenges Jones to push the possibilities and innovations of such conventional materials and construction practices.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAdding to DJA\u2019s design philosophy, they are well recognized for their feasibility in both economics and physical craftsmanship. DJA prides itself on delivering high quality design that challenge but also push traditional methods of construction.<ref name=\":5\" /> Ever since Jones\u2019 first project, he developed an appreciation for physical craftsmanship and construction that he further encourages and promotes through his own designs.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> This is done through the practice\u2019s intricate detail design work together with the strong realization of construction realities.<ref name=\":5\" /> Together with strong relationships with local builders and labourers, the bespoke design work is still intended to be able to be carried out by the majority of construction workers.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nIn response to the scale and level of detailed work produced by DJA, it has always been an intensive studio culture where everyone ranging from interns to seniors are all in charge of leading 2-3 projects each. Jones believes this allows projects and workers to have a better rounded perspective rather than more traditional hierarchies seen in other firms.<ref name=\":1\" /> Starting at a 9 person office, Jones\u2019 states that he does not intend to surpass 15 people as the focus and intimacy of project details and design will be lost which goes against his practice\u2019s philosophy.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Jones' personal design influences consist of a wide, ever-changing variety of architects but states that despite the immediate rotation, \"I often come back to earlier influences.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graymag.com/2019/05/13/architect-darcy-jones-chooses-paths-less-traveled/|title=Architect D\u2019Arcy Jones Chooses Paths Less Traveled|last=May 13|first=Kathrine Guzik|last2=2019|date=2019-05-13|website=GRAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Projects ==\n'''Friesen Wong House'''\n\nThe Friesen Wong House is a custom single family residential house that additionally features a pottery studio and shop area.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/friesen-wong-house|title=Friesen Wong House|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The siting of the house takes place on a rocky hilltop that overlooks the topography of the surrounding [[Kalamalka Lake Provincial Park and Protected Area|Kalamalka Lake Provincial Park]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> The house was designed bespoke to cater towards the lifestyle of the owners Jon Friesen and Silping Wong.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dwell.com/home/friesen-wong-residence-d2020448|title=Friesen-Wong Residence Modern Home in British Columbia, Canada by\u2026|website=Dwell|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> This meant a design integrated within nature that responded to their lifestyle surrounding heavily on outdoor activities.<ref name=\":11\" /> Jon states that the was imagined to be an \"extension of the park\" where the house grew out of the land rather than being an object building that disrupted the landscape. Jon also states that the house was imagined to embody the surrounding park despite where you were located within the house, as if always \"walking around the park.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> Jones ultimately responds to this design vision by translating the house into a sturdy and tough built form to respond to the site but also gracefully being sited within the landscape.<ref name=\":11\" /> The house focuses an emphasis on innovative sustainable and economic features. A prominent concrete cantilever structure together with structural insulated panel building technology (SIPS) was designed to work in tandem with small steel pins to help support the floor slab and ultimately create a thermal break to ensure a continuous insulation layer.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Other structural innovations include a concrete block column that was used hollowed out to render a fireplace on the interior.<ref name=\":11\" /> On the interior, \"saddlebag\" storage units increase temperature control and have allowed cutback on glazing costs.<ref name=\":11\" /> For materiality, the house chooses to showcase its permanence with materials like steel, concrete, and charred wood that require little upkeep.<ref name=\":11\" /> The cladding was done in a Douglas Fir wood that is native to the region. Together with his father, Jon personally charred the wood using a technique called traditional Japanese wood preserving technique called [[Yakisugi|shou sugi ban]] to protect against weathering and insect erosion.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Frieson Wong House went on to win a handful of awards, most notably the Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia Awards in Architecture (2017).<ref name=\":10\" /> \n\n\n\n'''Double Header House'''\n\nThe Double Header House is single residential housing project designed to house 3 generations of one family under one roof. The house is split into two main units: one housing the main family and kids, and the other housing the grandparents, and public and private access to both units through a communal staircase.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.azuremagazine.com/article/darcy-jones-creates-a-multi-gen-marvel-in-victoria-b-c/|title=D'Arcy Jones Creates a Multi-Gen Marvel in Victoria, B.C.|date=2019-11-25|website=Azure Magazine|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> This unique living condition was determined by the local zoning in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria BC]] that prevented the development of a duplex on the site, but instead allowed for a main building accompanied with a secondary suite.<ref name=\":12\" /> The plan layout consists of both living suits to be be facing each other in a north-south orientation rather than a typical side-by-side layout seen in duplexes. This would allow both spaces to feel a sense of width close to a \"typical house\".<ref name=\":12\" /> What is most unique about the house is the origami like metal overhangs identical on both facades. This important design element helps mitigate sunlight coming into the house but still provides enough light into the interior. This overhang also helps with the privacy of people looking in.<ref name=\":12\" />\n \n\n\n'''Deep Cove House'''\n\nThe Deep Cove House is single residential house located in [[Deep Cove, North Vancouver]]. As Jones describes, the house was designed to be \"part look-out tower, part courtyard and part land form.\" <ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/11/07/deep-cove-house-darcy-jones-architects-vancouver/|title=D'Arcy Jones defines Deep Cove House with slanted wood-clad walls|date=2019-11-07|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.dal.ca/news/deep-cove-house-by-darcy-jones-beds-97-architects-selected-as-one-of-dezeens-top-10-canadian-houses-of-2019/|title=D'Arcy Jones (BEDS'97) Architects takes 2019 top magazine honours!|date=2019-12-17|website=Dalhousie Alumni|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/deep-cove-house|title=Deep Cove House|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The house is sited on top a clifftop in Deep Cove where ultimately this multi-functioning form and program came to realization. The exterior of the house is designed with contrasting facades: the public street-facing one being completely closed off with no glazing versus the backside with extensive wrap-around windows.<ref name=\":13\" /> This is to allow for minimal views into the house from the public and nearby commercial streets and maximizes the expansive views overlooking the surrounding forest and water.<ref name=\":13\" /> The building's sharp angles also help combat and minimize exterior glare and promote water runoff.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\" />. The interior was designed around a minimalist and modest yet flexible plan.<ref name=\":13\" /> This meant a simple grey-scale colour palette with minimalistic furniture. This was designed with inspiration from older architectural ideals of creating rooms with no given program and instead allow a multitude of programs/uses to form to a generic room.<ref name=\":13\" /> This would ultimately allow for the exterior views to be the highlight rather than interior.<ref name=\":13\" /> \n\nThe Deep Cove House was selected in 2019 as one of [[Dezeen]]'s Top 10 Canadian Houses.<ref name=\":14\" />\n== Awards and Achievements ==\nD\u2019arcy Jones Architects has been the recipient of many awards and achievements. In recent years, the office together with many of their projects have been widely published and featured in books, journals, articles, magazines, and interviews. <ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/about|title=Bibliography|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nThe practice has received awards through the firm itself as well as the projects they have done. These include:  \n\n* '''RAIC Emerging Architectural Practice Award (2017) -''' A highly regarded award that recognizes firm principles and their representation of distinguished architectural projects. Criteria for such recognition includes project and design quality, innovations, public recognition and client service quality. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/news/article/149995826/d-arcy-jones-architecture-named-raic-2017-emerging-architectural-practice-winner|title=D'Arcy Jones Architecture named RAIC 2017 Emerging Architectural Practice winner|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n* '''AIBC Emerging Firm Award (2017)''' <ref name=\":1\" /> \n* '''Ronald J. Thom Award for Early Design Achievement (2014) -''' presented to architects who showcase innovative talent and architectural potential in the field. Presented to architects who are in the earlier parts of their career. <ref name=\":7\" /> \n* '''Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia Awards in Architecture (2017) -''' local award given to BC architects that recognizes design excellence in recently completed projects. In the case of this award, the ''<u>Friesen Wong House</u>'' was recognized. <ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://awards.aibc.ca/award-recipients/2017-recipients/|title=2017 Recipients {{!}} Architectural Awards|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n* '''Arthur Erickson Memorial Award (2010) -''' the first year of this award conception, Jones won the award that honours Arthur Erickson who was a Canadian architect integral in Canadian architecture and someone who inspired many. Given to designers who are just emerging in recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/d-arcy-jones-wins-first-arthur-erickson-memorial-award/|title=D'Arcy Jones wins first Arthur Erickson Memorial Award|date=2010-09-17|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n* '''Canadian Architect Award of Merit (2015) -''' award for the 'Ha-Ha House' project.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n* '''Canadian Architect Award of Merit (2009) -''' award for the 'The Cowboy' project.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\n== <u>References</u> ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox architect\n| name = D'Arcy Jones\n| practice = D'Arcy Jones Architects\n| significant_buildings = \n| significant_projects = \n| website = https://www.darcyjones.com/\n| birth_place = Fort St.John, British Columbia\n| education = University of Manitoba\n}}\n\nD\u2019Arcy Jones is a Canadian [[architect]] and the founding principle of [https://www.darcyjones.com/ D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects] (DJA) (formerly known as D\u2019Arcy Jones Architecture), a studio practice based out of [[Vancouver|Vancouver British Columbia, Canada]]. DJA\u2019s portfolio consists of completed and ongoing projects focusing greatly within their local area of British Columbia while some reside as far as Ontario, Washington, California, and Switzerland.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reminetwork.com/articles/emerging-talent-of-architect-darcy-jones/|title=The emerging talent of architect D'Arcy Jones - REMI Network|website=REMINET|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/raic-awards-excellence-emerging-architectural-practice-award/|title=RAIC Awards of Excellence: Emerging Architectural Practice Award|date=2017-05-12|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects focuses mainly on small scale boutique residential homes, many of which have brought national and international recognition for the practice.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://raic.org/awards/emerging-architectural-practice-award-%E2%80%94-2017-recipient|website=raic.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects in tandem with Jones himself has award-winning work that has been widely published in magazines, newspapers, books, journals and interviews. His emerging recognition has gained him respect from awards won through his adaptive reuse approach on existing Vancouver houses.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Canadian Modern Architecture|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|year=2019|isbn=9781616896454|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> The practice and specific projects have received many awards highlighting things like design excellence and emerging firm recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aibc.memberpro.net/main/body.cfm?menu=directory&submenu=directoryBusiness&page_no=108&records_perpage_qy=1&city_nm=&company_nm=d&mode=search&searchField=company_nm&search_value=d&record_id=108&table_id=2381&total_pages=53&total_records=523&more_pages=42&more_records=413|title=Architectural Institute of BC|website=aibc.memberpro.net|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/darcy-jones-wins-ronald-j-thom-award-for-early-design-achievement/|title=D'Arcy Jones wins Ronald J. Thom Award for Early Design Achievement|date=2014-07-22|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.dal.ca/news/alumni/big-win-for-darcy-jones-architecture/|title=Big win for Vancouver-based company D\u2019Arcy Jones Architecture (DJA)|date=2017-06-01|website=Dalhousie Alumni|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Jones himself is an architect registration in the provinces of in BC ([[Architectural Institute of British Columbia|AIBC]]), Manitoba ([https://www.mbarchitects.org/ MAA]), Ontario ([[Ontario Association of Architects|OAA]]) and a member of the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada]] (MRAIC). <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/copy-of-people|title=People|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\n== Early Life and Career ==\nD\u2019arcy Jones is a Canadian native, born and raised in British Columbia. Although born in [[Fort St. John, British Columbia|Fort St. John]] Jones spent his early life growing up in [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]]. From early on, Jones developed both an artistic interest in drawing and the physical act of building. Jones\u2019 interest in physical design continued to grow during highschool grade 11 when he was enrolled in a class that taught drafting.<ref name=\":1\" /> This eventually drove him to pursue post secondary to achieve both a bachelors and a masters degree. In 1995, Jones received a bachelor's degree in Environmental Design at the [[University of Manitoba]] followed by a bachelor of Environmental Design Studies at the [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] (TUNS)(which merged into what is now [[Dalhousie University]]). Shortly after, he returned back to the University of Manitoba where he completed his masters in Architecture in 1999.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nDuring his time still as an undergrad student in university, Jones was already designing architecture that made its way into physical realization. His first real project was a commission done in 1996 by his own parents asking him to design their home.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/features/article/150068361/vancouver-based-d-arcy-jones-architecture-stays-small-to-maintain-intimacy-with-their-work|title=Vancouver Based D'Arcy Jones Architecture Stays Small to Maintain Intimacy With Their Work|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> During this time, Jones claims that the project made him appreciate and \u201cfall in love\u201d with factors that were not taught in architecture school, such as the practical and technical characteristics of architecture.<ref name=\":5\" /> The success of this solo project caused him to find his own practice after graduating from masters in 1999, where he would officially start practicing alone from the years 2000-2005.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> During these early times as a solo practice, Jones was based out of his personal house located in Vancouver\u2019s west end.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nProfessionally, Jones followed a path that was considered abnormal and non-traditional. As typically seen in Canada (where he would eventually practice) and many other parts of the world, the licensing process remains very strict and orderly in terms of how to achieve official registration as a practicing architect. With respect to contemporary licensing, the process follows a structure where an individual with a Masters of Architecture degree will work under the title of \u2018[[Intern architect|intern]]\u2019 through already established firms. Instead, Jones founded his own practice,\u00a0right after graduating in 1999 and has been self-employed ever since.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Unlike in a normal intern employment situation where a registered architect will supervise and sign off on one\u2019s \u2018working hours,\u2019 Jones never traditionally interned and obtained his hours remaining as a solo practice by collaborations and joint ventures. He states in an interview that he used joint ventures with registered architects as a means to carry out projects and complete his \u2018internship.\u2019<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAfter 5 years of solo practice, Jones moved the practice from his own home into an office space in Mount Pleasant in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" /> From here Jones officially founded D\u2019Arcy Jones Architecture (currently known as D\u2019Arcy Jones Architects) where he expanded his studio size to a humble 9 person team including himself.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Although technically involved with architectural practice since the conception of his firm in 2000, Jones achieved being a registered architect in 2013.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAs an established architect and practice, Jones actively involves himself and contributes within the field of architecture through talk panels, design competitions, lecturing, juries, and teaching. In 2015, Jones was taken on by the University of British Columbia to be an adjunct professor within their schools of Architecture and Landscape Architecture where things like studio teaching, critiquing and being a thesis advisor are carried out.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Most recently, he was invited by the [[University of Calgary]] as a guest critic for students\u2019 within the Faculty of Environmental Design.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Design Approach ==\nD\u2019Arcy Jones has always been recognized for his boutique residential houses ever since completing his very first project as a student. To this day, Jones has gained respect through his most notable works and completed projects which fall largely under the typology of single residential housing.<ref name=\":6\" /> Alongside the natural evolution of the firm, projects encompassing a broader typology but keeping in similar scale include galleries, renovations, interiors, commercial and gallery spaces.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nJones\u2019 projects focus greatly on the exploration and combination of program together with proportion, and how site and materiality shape it. Furthermore, these aspects help DJA explore the technicalities of details and construction as integral parts of the design process.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nJones has always been a proponent of the deeper characteristics of sustainability and inherently is seen translated into DJA\u2019s project designs and philosophies.<ref name=\":5\" /> As seen through Vancouver's First Shaughnessy Design Panel, Jones was actively involved representing the [[Architectural Institute of British Columbia]] ([[Architectural Institute of British Columbia|AIBC]]). This was a panel that fundamentally helped establish Vancouver\u2019s prohibition against demolishing heritage houses that dated before the 1940\u2019s.<ref name=\":0\" /> From a design perspective, DJA\u2019s philosophy encourages the integration of modern expression by using existing buildings as a starting point or blank canvas.<ref name=\":1\" /> In many of DJA\u2019s projects, intensive renovations and adaptive reuse of existing homes seems to be where opportunities in showcasing sustainability take place through innovation and thoughtful recycling.<ref name=\":2\" /> As stated by Jones, \"the greenest building is the one already built,\" and this further encourages their projects to address material efficiently and re imagine innovative sustainable designs to introduce things like passive cooling and breezes to save energy.<ref name=\":5\" /> Through their designs, Jones\u2019 also encourages design sustainability through key factors like favoring common and local building materials over nonnative and foreign ones.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> This ultimately challenges Jones to push the possibilities and innovations of such conventional materials and construction practices.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAdding to DJA\u2019s design philosophy, they are well recognized for their feasibility in both economics and physical craftsmanship. DJA prides itself on delivering high quality design that challenge but also push traditional methods of construction.<ref name=\":5\" /> Ever since Jones\u2019 first project, he developed an appreciation for physical craftsmanship and construction that he further encourages and promotes through his own designs.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> This is done through the practice\u2019s intricate detail design work together with the strong realization of construction realities.<ref name=\":5\" /> Together with strong relationships with local builders and labourers, the bespoke design work is still intended to be able to be carried out by the majority of construction workers.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nIn response to the scale and level of detailed work produced by DJA, it has always been an intensive studio culture where everyone ranging from interns to seniors are all in charge of leading 2-3 projects each. Jones believes this allows projects and workers to have a better rounded perspective rather than more traditional hierarchies seen in other firms.<ref name=\":1\" /> Starting at a 9 person office, Jones\u2019 states that he does not intend to surpass 15 people as the focus and intimacy of project details and design will be lost which goes against his practice\u2019s philosophy.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Jones' personal design influences consist of a wide, ever-changing variety of architects but states that despite the immediate rotation, \"I often come back to earlier influences.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graymag.com/2019/05/13/architect-darcy-jones-chooses-paths-less-traveled/|title=Architect D\u2019Arcy Jones Chooses Paths Less Traveled|last=May 13|first=Kathrine Guzik|last2=2019|date=2019-05-13|website=GRAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Projects ==\n'''Friesen Wong House'''\n\nThe Friesen Wong House is a custom single family residential house that additionally features a pottery studio and shop area.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/friesen-wong-house|title=Friesen Wong House|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The siting of the house takes place on a rocky hilltop that overlooks the topography of the surrounding [[Kalamalka Lake Provincial Park and Protected Area|Kalamalka Lake Provincial Park]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> The house was designed bespoke to cater towards the lifestyle of the owners Jon Friesen and Silping Wong.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dwell.com/home/friesen-wong-residence-d2020448|title=Friesen-Wong Residence Modern Home in British Columbia, Canada by\u2026|website=Dwell|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> This meant a design integrated within nature that responded to their lifestyle surrounding heavily on outdoor activities.<ref name=\":11\" /> Jon states that the was imagined to be an \"extension of the park\" where the house grew out of the land rather than being an object building that disrupted the landscape. Jon also states that the house was imagined to embody the surrounding park despite where you were located within the house, as if always \"walking around the park.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> Jones ultimately responds to this design vision by translating the house into a sturdy and tough built form to respond to the site but also gracefully being sited within the landscape.<ref name=\":11\" /> The house focuses an emphasis on innovative sustainable and economic features. A prominent concrete cantilever structure together with structural insulated panel building technology (SIPS) was designed to work in tandem with small steel pins to help support the floor slab and ultimately create a thermal break to ensure a continuous insulation layer.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Other structural innovations include a concrete block column that was used hollowed out to render a fireplace on the interior.<ref name=\":11\" /> On the interior, \"saddlebag\" storage units increase temperature control and have allowed cutback on glazing costs.<ref name=\":11\" /> For materiality, the house chooses to showcase its permanence with materials like steel, concrete, and charred wood that require little upkeep.<ref name=\":11\" /> The cladding was done in a Douglas Fir wood that is native to the region. Together with his father, Jon personally charred the wood using a technique called traditional Japanese wood preserving technique called [[Yakisugi|shou sugi ban]] to protect against weathering and insect erosion.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Frieson Wong House went on to win a handful of awards, most notably the Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia Awards in Architecture (2017).<ref name=\":10\" /> \n\n\n\n'''Double Header House'''\n\nThe Double Header House is single residential housing project designed to house 3 generations of one family under one roof. The house is split into two main units: one housing the main family and kids, and the other housing the grandparents, and public and private access to both units through a communal staircase.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.azuremagazine.com/article/darcy-jones-creates-a-multi-gen-marvel-in-victoria-b-c/|title=D'Arcy Jones Creates a Multi-Gen Marvel in Victoria, B.C.|date=2019-11-25|website=Azure Magazine|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> This unique living condition was determined by the local zoning in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria BC]] that prevented the development of a duplex on the site, but instead allowed for a main building accompanied with a secondary suite.<ref name=\":12\" /> The plan layout consists of both living suits to be be facing each other in a north-south orientation rather than a typical side-by-side layout seen in duplexes. This would allow both spaces to feel a sense of width close to a \"typical house\".<ref name=\":12\" /> What is most unique about the house is the origami like metal overhangs identical on both facades. This important design element helps mitigate sunlight coming into the house but still provides enough light into the interior. This overhang also helps with the privacy of people looking in.<ref name=\":12\" />\n \n\n\n'''Deep Cove House'''\n\nThe Deep Cove House is single residential house located in [[Deep Cove, North Vancouver]]. As Jones describes, the house was designed to be \"part look-out tower, part courtyard and part land form.\" <ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/11/07/deep-cove-house-darcy-jones-architects-vancouver/|title=D'Arcy Jones defines Deep Cove House with slanted wood-clad walls|date=2019-11-07|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.dal.ca/news/deep-cove-house-by-darcy-jones-beds-97-architects-selected-as-one-of-dezeens-top-10-canadian-houses-of-2019/|title=D'Arcy Jones (BEDS'97) Architects takes 2019 top magazine honours!|date=2019-12-17|website=Dalhousie Alumni|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/deep-cove-house|title=Deep Cove House|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The house is sited on top a clifftop in Deep Cove where ultimately this multi-functioning form and program came to realization. The exterior of the house is designed with contrasting facades: the public street-facing one being completely closed off with no glazing versus the backside with extensive wrap-around windows.<ref name=\":13\" /> This is to allow for minimal views into the house from the public and nearby commercial streets and maximizes the expansive views overlooking the surrounding forest and water.<ref name=\":13\" /> The building's sharp angles also help combat and minimize exterior glare and promote water runoff.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\" />. The interior was designed around a minimalist and modest yet flexible plan.<ref name=\":13\" /> This meant a simple grey-scale colour palette with minimalistic furniture. This was designed with inspiration from older architectural ideals of creating rooms with no given program and instead allow a multitude of programs/uses to form to a generic room.<ref name=\":13\" /> This would ultimately allow for the exterior views to be the highlight rather than interior.<ref name=\":13\" /> \n\nThe Deep Cove House was selected in 2019 as one of [[Dezeen]]'s Top 10 Canadian Houses.<ref name=\":14\" />\n== Awards and Achievements ==\nD\u2019arcy Jones Architects has been the recipient of many awards and achievements. In recent years, the office together with many of their projects have been widely published and featured in books, journals, articles, magazines, and interviews. <ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.darcyjones.com/about|title=Bibliography|website=D'Arcy Jones Architects|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nThe practice has received awards through the firm itself as well as the projects they have done. These include:  \n\n* '''RAIC Emerging Architectural Practice Award (2017) -''' A highly regarded award that recognizes firm principles and their representation of distinguished architectural projects. Criteria for such recognition includes project and design quality, innovations, public recognition and client service quality. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/news/article/149995826/d-arcy-jones-architecture-named-raic-2017-emerging-architectural-practice-winner|title=D'Arcy Jones Architecture named RAIC 2017 Emerging Architectural Practice winner|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n* '''AIBC Emerging Firm Award (2017)''' <ref name=\":1\" /> \n* '''Ronald J. Thom Award for Early Design Achievement (2014) -''' presented to architects who showcase innovative talent and architectural potential in the field. Presented to architects who are in the earlier parts of their career. <ref name=\":7\" /> \n* '''Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia Awards in Architecture (2017) -''' local award given to BC architects that recognizes design excellence in recently completed projects. In the case of this award, the ''<u>Friesen Wong House</u>'' was recognized. <ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://awards.aibc.ca/award-recipients/2017-recipients/|title=2017 Recipients {{!}} Architectural Awards|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n* '''Arthur Erickson Memorial Award (2010) -''' the first year of this award conception, Jones won the award that honours Arthur Erickson who was a Canadian architect integral in Canadian architecture and someone who inspired many. Given to designers who are just emerging in recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/d-arcy-jones-wins-first-arthur-erickson-memorial-award/|title=D'Arcy Jones wins first Arthur Erickson Memorial Award|date=2010-09-17|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n* '''Canadian Architect Award of Merit (2015) -''' award for the 'Ha-Ha House' project.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n* '''Canadian Architect Award of Merit (2009) -''' award for the 'The Cowboy' project.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\n== <u>References</u> ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Kolbie.Fung", "label": "safe", "comment": "added date and citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%27Arcy_Jones"}
