{"title_page": "Dell FX100", "text_new": "The [[Dell]] '''FX100''' is the company's first [[thin client]], advertised as a \"zero client\". It works in conjunction with [[VMware View]] 4.0, and uses the [[PC-over-IP]] network communication protocol with a server.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/03/03/dell_fx100_pc_over_ip/ |title=Dell flogs its 'zero client' |author=  Austin Modine |work= The Register |date= March 3, 2010 |accessdate= August 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/1594719/dell-launches-zero-client |title=Dell launches a zero client |work=The Inquirer |date= March 3, 2010 |author= Spencer Dalziel |accessdate= August 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9163799/Dell_is_latest_to_unveil_zero_client_hardware_for_VDI |title=Dell is latest to unveil 'zero client' hardware for VDI |author= Eric Lai |work= ComputerWorld | date= March 2, 2010 |accessdate= August 8, 2011 }}</ref>\nThe product was announced in March 2010, and is sold through the \"large enterprise\" business unit.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Top 10 Cheapest Wordpress Web Hosting Plans \n |work=ConceptsMadeEasy.com \n |url=https://conceptsmadeeasy.com/top-10-cheapest-wordpress-web-hosting-plans-of-shine-it-solutions/ \n |accessdate=April 12, 2019 \n}}{{|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Desktop virtualization]]\n* [[Sun Ray]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Comp-hardware-stub}}\n\n{{Dell Inc}}\n\n[[Category:Dell hardware]]\n[[Category:Thin clients]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Dell]] '''FX100''' is the company's first [[thin client]], advertised as a \"zero client\". It works in conjunction with [[VMware View]] 4.0, and uses the [[PC-over-IP]] network communication protocol with a server.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/03/03/dell_fx100_pc_over_ip/ |title=Dell flogs its 'zero client' |author=  Austin Modine |work= The Register |date= March 3, 2010 |accessdate= August 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/1594719/dell-launches-zero-client |title=Dell launches a zero client |work=The Inquirer |date= March 3, 2010 |author= Spencer Dalziel |accessdate= August 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9163799/Dell_is_latest_to_unveil_zero_client_hardware_for_VDI |title=Dell is latest to unveil 'zero client' hardware for VDI |author= Eric Lai |work= ComputerWorld | date= March 2, 2010 |accessdate= August 8, 2011 }}</ref>\nThe product was announced in March 2010, and is sold through the \"large enterprise\" business unit.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Dell FX100 \n |work=commercial web site \n |url=http://www.dell.com/us/enterprise/p/dell-fx100/ \n |accessdate=August 8, 2011 \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Desktop virtualization]]\n* [[Sun Ray]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Comp-hardware-stub}}\n\n{{Dell Inc}}\n\n[[Category:Dell hardware]]\n[[Category:Thin clients]]\n", "name_user": "Concepts Made Easy", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dell_FX100"}
{"title_page": "Aporodoris", "text_new": "{{Automatic_taxobox\n| image =\n| image_caption = \n| taxon = Aporodoris\n| authority=Ihering, 1886<ref>Ihering H. von (1886). Zur kenntnis der Nudibranchien der brasilianischen kuste. Jahrb\u00fccher der Deutschen Malakozoologischen Gesellschaft 13 (3): 223-240, [https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/16355937 page 238]</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Aporodoris''''' is a [[genus]] of [[sea slug]]s, dorid [[nudibranch]], shell-less [[marine (ocean)|marine]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusc]]s in the family [[Discorididae]].<ref name=\"WoRMS\">MolluscaBase (2018). [http://www.molluscabase.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=531807 ''Aporodoris'' Ihering, 1886.] Accessed on 2019-02-02.</ref>\n\n==Taxonomic status==\nVald\u00e9s & Gosliner (2001<ref>Vald\u00e9s \u00c1. & Gosliner T.M. 2001. ''Systematics and phylogeny of the caryophyllidia-bearing dorids (Mollusca, Nudibranchia), with the description of a new genus and four new species from Indo-Pacific deep waters.'' Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 133(2): 103-198 page(s): 170-171)</ref> synonymised '''''Aporodoris''''' with ''[[Taringa (gastropod)|Taringa]]'', invoking ICZN Art. 23.9 to designate ''Aporodoris'' a ''[[nomen oblitum]]'' and ''Taringa'' Er. Marcus, 1955 a ''[[nomen protectum]]''.\n\nDayrat, 2010\n<ref name=\"Dayrat\">[http://campillos.ucmerced.edu/~bdayrat/PDF%20of%20Papers/Dayrat%202010%20PCAS%20HR.pdf  Dayrat B. 2010. A monographic revision of discodorid sea slugs (Gastropoda, Opisthobranchia, Nudibranchia, Doridina). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, vol. 61, suppl. I, 1-403, 382 figs.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908235123/http://campillos.ucmerced.edu/~bdayrat/PDF%20of%20Papers/Dayrat%202010%20PCAS%20HR.pdf |date=2015-09-08 }}</ref> made the following argument for reinstatement of ''Aporodoris'':\n\n<blockquote>SUPRA-SPECIFIC RELATIONSHIPS. Here, two questions are discussed: 1) the generic affinities proposed for ''millegrana'', and 2) the valid name of the clade it belongs to, knowing that ''millegrana'' is the type species of the genus name ''Aporodoris'' von lhering 1886, by original designation. Bergh (1878a) re-allocated ''millegrana'' to ''Archidoris'' and then (Bergh 1894) to ''Thordisa'' with no explanation. Von lhering (1886) created a new generic name for ''millegrana'', ''Aporodoris''. The genus name ''Aporodoris'' was then used to describe several new species: ''Aporodoris rubra'' Bergh, 1905; ''Aporodoris risbeci'' Marcus and Marcus, 1967; and ''Aporodoris merria'' Burn, 1973. Thompson and Brown (1981) decided to re-allocate ''millegrana'' to ''Discodoris'' (Thompson classified all basal discodorids in ''Discodoris''). Then, more recently, Valdes and Gosliner (2001) rightly argued that ''Aporodoris'' von lhering, 1886, and ''Taringa'' Marcus, 1955, are two synonyms, and that ''millegrana'' belongs to ''Taringa'' species (as shown in the present phylogenetic analysis).</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>The next question is: Which name should we use for that clade, ''Taringa'' or ''Aporodoris''? The older name, ''Aporodoris'', should have priority over the younger name, ''Taringa''. Valdes and Gosliner (2001) argued that in this case, however, the ICZN Article 23.9 (not 23.9.2) applies and that the younger name should be regarded as valid. However, Article 23.9 actually does not apply here. According to Article 23.9, prevailing usage can be maintained only if two conditions are met (described in 23.9.1), one of which (23.9.1.1) is that the senior synonym must not have been used as a valid name after 1899. Although Valdes and Gosliner (2001) thought that ''Aporodoris'' had not been used as a valid name since 1899, three new species names were created in ''Aporodoris'' since 1899 (see above), and several authors used the binomial ''Aporodoris millegrana'' as valid (Eliot 1910b; Pruvot-Fol 1954a; Bouchet and Tardy 1976). Therefore ''Aporodoris'' is a valid name, regardless of whether ''Taringa'' has been widely used or not.</blockquote>\n\nIn addition, but not noted by Dayrat, the combination ''Aporodoris millegrana'' was treated as the valid combination for this species between 1910 (Eliot, 1910b) and 1981 (Thompson and Brown, 1981) in listings of the British molluscan fauna (Winckworth, 1932;<ref>Winckworth, R. 1932. The British Marine Mollusca. Journal of Conchology, 19 (7): 211-252.</ref> White, 1937;<ref>White, K. M. 1938. The nomenclature of British Nudibranch Mollusca by Alder and Hancock and by Eliot correlated with that of British Marine Mollusca by Winckworth. Journal of Conchology, 21(1), 14-19.</ref> Turk, 1973 <ref>Turk S.M., 1973. Concordance to the field card for British Marine Mollusca. Conchological Society of Great Britain and Ireland, pp.66.</ref>)\n\nHowever, according to [http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosted-sites/iczn/code/index.jsp?article=23 Article 23.10] of the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]] (1999), this action stands and ''Taringa'' should be used as the valid name until such time as the Commission rules otherwise.\n\n==Description==\nThis genus is characterized by the presence of a membranaceous penial cuticle.\n\n''[[Taringa]]'' is placed in the family [[Discodorididae]].\n\n== Species ==\nSpecies in the genus ''Aporodoris'' includes:\n* ''[[Aporodoris merria]]'' <small>Burn, 1973</small>\n* ''[[Aporodoris millegrana]]'' <small>(Alder & Hancock, 1854)</small>\n;Species brought into synonymy:\n* ''Apodoris fanabensis''  <small>Ortea & Martinez, 1992</small> : synonym of ''Aporodoris millegrana'' <small>(Alder & Hancock, 1854)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Wikispecies-inline|Aporodoris|''Aporodoris''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2157779}}\n\n[[Category:Dorididae]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic_taxobox\n| image =\n| image_caption = \n| taxon = Aporodoris\n| authority=Ihering, 1886<ref>Ihering H. von (1886). Zur kenntnis der Nudibranchien der brasilianischen kuste. Jahrb\u00fccher der Deutschen Malakozoologischen Gesellschaft 13 (3): 223-240, [https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/16355937 page 238]</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Aporodoris''''' is a [[genus]] of [[sea slug]]s, dorid [[nudibranch]], shell-less [[marine (ocean)|marine]] [[gastropod]] [[mollusc]]s in the family [[Discorididae]].<ref name=\"WoRMS\">MolluscaBase (2018). [http://www.molluscabase.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=531807 ''Aporodoris'' Ihering, 1886.] Accessed on 2019-02-02.</ref>\n\n==Taxonomic status==\nVald\u00e9s & Gosliner (2001<ref>Vald\u00e9s \u00c1. & Gosliner T.M. 2001. ''Systematics and phylogeny of the caryophyllidia-bearing dorids (Mollusca, Nudibranchia), with the description of a new genus and four new species from Indo-Pacific deep waters.'' Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 133(2): 103-198 page(s): 170-171)</ref> synonymised '''''Aporodoris''''' with ''[[Taringa (gastropod)|Taringa]]'', invoking ICZN Art. 23.9 to designate ''Aporodoris'' a ''[[nomen oblitum]]'' and ''Taringa'' Er. Marcus, 1955 a ''[[nomen protectum]]''.\n\nDayrat, 2010\n<ref name=\"Dayrat\">[http://campillos.ucmerced.edu/~bdayrat/PDF%20of%20Papers/Dayrat%202010%20PCAS%20HR.pdf  Dayrat B. 2010. A monographic revision of discodorid sea slugs (Gastropoda, Opisthobranchia, Nudibranchia, Doridina). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, vol. 61, suppl. I, 1-403, 382 figs.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908235123/http://campillos.ucmerced.edu/~bdayrat/PDF%20of%20Papers/Dayrat%202010%20PCAS%20HR.pdf |date=2015-09-08 }}</ref> made the following argument for reinstatement of ''Aporodoris'':\n\n<blockquote>SUPRA-SPECIFIC RELATIONSHIPS. Here, two questions are discussed: 1) the generic affinities proposed for ''millegrana'', and 2) the valid name of the clade it belongs to, knowing that ''millegrana'' is the type species of the genus name ''Aporodoris'' von lhering 1886, by original designation. Bergh (1878a) re-allocated ''millegrana'' to ''Archidoris'' and then (Bergh 1894) to ''Thordisa'' with no explanation. Von lhering (1886) created a new generic name for ''millegrana'', ''Aporodoris''. The genus name ''Aporodoris'' was then used to describe several new species: ''Aporodoris rubra'' Bergh, 1905; ''Aporodoris risbeci'' Marcus and Marcus, 1967; and ''Aporodoris merria'' Burn, 1973. Thompson and Brown (1981) decided to re-allocate ''millegrana'' to ''Discodoris'' (Thompson classified all basal discodorids in ''Discodoris''). Then, more recently, Valdes and Gosliner (2001) rightly argued that ''Aporodoris'' von lhering, 1886, and ''Taringa'' Marcus, 1955, are two synonyms, and that ''millegrana'' belongs to ''Taringa'' species (as shown in the present phylogenetic analysis).</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>The next question is: Which name should we use for that clade, ''Taringa'' or ''Aporodoris''? The older name, ''Aporodoris'', should have priority over the younger name, ''Taringa''. Valdes and Gosliner (2001) argued that in this case, however, the ICZN Article 23.9 (not 23.9.2) applies and that the younger name should be regarded as valid. However, Article 23.9 actually does not apply here. According to Article 23.9, prevailing usage can be maintained only if two conditions are met (described in 23.9.1), one of which (23.9.1.1) is that the senior synonym must not have been used as a valid name after 1899. Although Valdes and Gosliner (2001) thought that ''Aporodoris'' had not been used as a valid name since 1899, three new species names were created in ''Aporodoris'' since 1899 (see above), and several authors used the binomial ''Aporodoris millegrana'' as valid (Eliot 1910b; Pruvot-Fol 1954a; Bouchet and Tardy 1976). Therefore ''Aporodoris'' is a valid name, regardless of whether ''Taringa'' has been widely used or not.</blockquote>\n\nIn addition, but not noted by Dayrat, the combination ''Aporodoris millegrana'' was treated as the valid combination for this species between 1910 (Eliot, 1910b) and 1981 (Thompson and Brown, 1981) in listings of the British molluscan fauna (Winckworth, 1932;<ref>Winckworth, R. 1932. The British Marine Mollusca. Journal of Conchology, 19 (7): 211-252.</ref> White, 1937;<ref>White, K. M. 1938. The nomenclature of British Nudibranch Mollusca by Alder and Hancock and by Eliot correlated with that of British Marine Mollusca by Winckworth. Journal of Conchology, 21(1), 14-19.</ref> Turk, 1973 <ref>Turk S.M., 1973. Concordance to the field card for British Marine Mollusca. Conchological Society of Great Britain and Ireland, pp.66.</ref>)\n\nHowever according to [http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosted-sites/iczn/code/index.jsp?article=23 Article 23.10] of the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]] (1999), this action stands and ''Taringa'' should be used as the valid name until such time as the Commission rules otherwise.\n\n==Description==\nThis genus is characterized by the presence of a membranaceous penial cuticle.\n\n''[[Taringa]]'' is placed in the family [[Discodorididae]].\n\n== Species ==\nSpecies in the genus ''Aporodoris'' includes:\n* ''[[Aporodoris merria]]'' <small>Burn, 1973</small>\n* ''[[Aporodoris millegrana]]'' <small>(Alder & Hancock, 1854)</small>\n;Species brought into synonymy:\n* ''Apodoris fanabensis''  <small>Ortea & Martinez, 1992</small> : synonym of ''Aporodoris millegrana'' <small>(Alder & Hancock, 1854)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Wikispecies-inline|Aporodoris|''Aporodoris''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2157779}}\n\n[[Category:Dorididae]]\n", "name_user": "Josve05a", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Spelling and typography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aporodoris"}
{"title_page": "Mauser Model 1908", "text_new": "{{about|the rifle produced for Brazil|the Serbian Mauser M1908|Mauser Model 1895#Serbian M1899}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Mauser Model 1908\n| image=File:Mauser-1908.jpg\n|caption= A Mauser Model 1908\n| image_size = 325\n|origin=Germany\n|type=[[Bolt-action]] [[rifle]]\n|service= 1908-present\n|used_by=[[Brazil]]<br>[[Uruguay]]<br>[[Dominican Republic]]\n|manufacturer= [[Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken|DWM]]<br>[[IMBEL|Itajuba arms factory]]\n|wars= [[Contestado War]]<br>[[Canga\u00e7o]] conflict<br>[[Dominican Civil War]]<br>[[Araguaia Guerrilla War]]\n|is_ranged=yes\n|design_date=\n|production_date=1908-1968\n|variants=Model 1908/34<br>Model 1935<br>M1949<br>M954<br>M968\n|number= \n|weight={{convert|3.8|kg|lbs}}\n|length={{convert|125|cm|in}}\n|part_length={{convert|74.3|cm|in}}\n|cartridge=[[7\u00d757mm Mauser]]<br>\n|action=[[Bolt-action]]\n|velocity=\n|range=\n|feed=5-round [[stripper clip]], internal [[Magazine (firearm)|magazine]]\n|sights= [[Iron sight]]s adjustable to {{convert|2000|m|yd}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Mauser Model 1908''' were series of [[Gewehr 98]] pattern bolt-action rifles. First produced by [[Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken]] (DWM) and [[Mauser]], they were exported to [[Uruguay]] and [[Brazil]]. In this latter country, [[IMBEL|Itajuba arms factory]] produced upgraded versions until the rifle was replaced by the [[FN FAL]].\n\n== Design ==\n=== Model 1908 ===\nThe Model 1908 rifle was a copy of the Mauser Gewehr 98, chambered in [[7\u00d757mm Mauser]]{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=65}} and with a simple tangent-leaf sight and a longer upper hand-guard.{{sfn|Out|1992|p=17}} A variant was also shortened to a {{convert|1.19|m|in|abbr=on}}-short rifle configuration.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=66}}\n\n=== Models 1935 and 08/34 ===\n[[File:Minist\u00e9rio agracia quase 300 personalidades com Ordem do M\u00e9rito da Defesa (9517559872).jpg|thumb|left|Brazilian soldiers in 2013 with Mauser 1935 or 08/34 short rifles.]]\nThe 7mm Mauser-made '''Model 1935 rifle''' was similar to the Model 1908 but featured grasping grooves.{{sfn|Out|1992|p=18}} A short rifle variant also existed.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=70}} Not to be confused with the Czech-made Model 1908/34 police carbine ([[Vz. 33#Vz. 12/33|Vz. 12/33]]), the '''Model 1908/34 short rifle''' was an upgraded version of the Model 1908 using local wood.<ref name=\"armasonline\"/>\n\n=== Later variants ===\nThe '''Mosquet\u00e3o Itajub\u00e1 M1949''' was a 08/34 short rifle chambered in [[.30-06 Springfield]]. The '''Mosquet\u00e3o Itajub\u00e1 M954'''<ref name=\"armasonline\">{{cite web|title=Fuz\u00eds Mauser no Brasil e as Espingardas da F\u00e1brica de Itajub\u00e1 (Rev. 2)|url=https://armasonline.org/armas-on-line/as-espingardas-da-fabrica-de-itajuba/|date=5 April 2011|first=Carlos F. P.|last= Neto|website=armasonline.org|language=pt}}</ref> was a variant fitted with a threaded muzzle, that enabled the use of a [[flash suppressor]] or of a [[rifle grenade|grenade launcher]]. Its buttplate was inspired by the one of the [[Gewehr 43]] (a copy of which was manufactured under the same {{ill|Itajub\u00e1 M954 Mosquet\u00e3o|pt}} designation).{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=73}}\n[[File:Carcar\u00e1 (4968096673).jpg|thumb|left|A Mauser M968 in a ceremony of the [[Military Police (Brazil)|Military Police]] in 2010.]]\nThe '''Mosquet\u00e3o 7,62mm Modelo 968'''<ref name=\"armasonline\"/> or M968 was one of the last Mauser service rifle produced. This rifle fired the [[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]] cartridge, a grenade launcher was fixed to its barrel and its stock was renforced with [[Natural rubber|rubber]]. These features were also used on the FN FAL,{{sfn|Out|1992|p=21}} hence the ''Mosquefal'' nickname.<ref name=\"armasonline\"/>\n\n== History and service ==\nLarge numbers of Model 1908 rifles and short rifles was purchased between 1908 and 1914.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=65}} While DWM was the main manufacturer, Mauser produced 100,000 Model 1908 with ''DWM Obendorf'' stamps.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=235}} Some Mauser 1908 saw combat during the [[Contestado War]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Aureliano|last= Pinto de Moura  |title=Semin\u00e1rio 100 Anos da Guerra do Contestado |date=1 August 2012|language=pt|url=https://www.mpsc.mp.br/noticias/seminario-100-anos-da-guerra-do-contestado|website=mpsc.mp.br|publisher=Minist\u00e9rio P\u00fablico de Santa Catarina}}</ref> Later, Model 1935 rifles and short rifles were purchased in unknown quantities from Mauser.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=69}}{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=70}} They were fielded against the [[Canga\u00e7o]] bandits.<ref name=\"armasonline\"/> To improve the country's independence from foreign suppliers, the Model 08/34 was produced in [[Itajuba]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=70}}\n\nUruguay received DWM-made Model 1908 rifles and short rifles before 1914 and used them into the 1950s.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=391}} Several ''Mystery Mausers'', similar to the Model 1908 but chambered in [[7.92\u00d757mm Mauser]], can be found with Arabic markings or an [[hexagram]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=405}}\n\nIn the early 1950s, surplus Brazilian 1908 rifles and short rifles were exported to the [[Dominican Republic]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=125}} The Brazilian markings were replaced by Dominican markings and the rifles were designated Model 1953.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=126}} During the US intervention in the [[Dominican Civil War]], these Mauser rifles were found to be very effective since they had longer range than the [[M16 rifle]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Power Pack: U.S. Intervention in the Dominican Republic, 1965-1966 |series=Leavenworth Papers, Number 15|last=Yates|first= Lawrence A. |date=July 1988|page= 123|publisher= [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]]|url= https://history.army.mil/html/bookshelves/resmat/dom_republic/Power_Pack-US_Intervention_Dominican_Republic_1965-1966.pdf}}</ref>\n\nPost-war, Itajuba plant produced the M1949 and M954 short rifles for the Brazilian armed forces.{{snf|Ball|2011|p=71}} During the [[Araguaia Guerrilla War]], the rebels were able to acquire 7.62 Mausers from the state police of [[Par\u00e1]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Conflito do Araguaia: Guerrilheiros e Soldados|first=Matias |last=Mendes|url=https://www.gentedeopiniao.com.br/colunista/matias-mendes/conflito-do-araguaia-guerrilheiros-e-soldados|website=Gente de Opini\u00e3o|language=pt|date=24 September 2012}}</ref> The M968 was produced for the Brazilian police.{{sfn|Out|1992|p=21}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ball|first=Robert W. D.|title=Mauser Military Rifles of the World|year=2011|location=Iola|publisher=Gun Digest Books|isbn=9781440228926|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine|title= Les Mauser br\u00e9siliens|first=Roger|last=Out|language=fr|date=December 1992|magazine=[[Gazette des Armes]]|issue=228|pages=17-21|ref=harv}}\n{{Mauser Firearms}}\n\n[[Category:7\u00d757mm Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Rifles of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1908]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the rifle produced for Brazil|the Serbian Mauser M1908|Mauser Model 1895#Serbian M1899}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Mauser Model 1908\n| image=File:Mauser-1908.jpg\n|caption= A Mauser Model 1908\n| image_size = 325\n|origin=Germany\n|type=[[Bolt-action]] [[rifle]]\n|service= 1908-present\n|used_by=[[Brazil]]<br>[[Uruguay]]<br>[[Dominican Republic]]\n|manufacturer= [[Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken|DWM]]<br>[[IMBEL|Itajuba arms factory]]\n|wars= [[Contestado War]]<br>[[Canga\u00e7o]] conflict<br>[[Dominican Civil War]]<br>[[Araguaia Guerrilla War]]\n|is_ranged=yes\n|design_date=\n|production_date=1908-1968\n|variants=Model 1908/34<br>Model 1935<br>M1949<br>M954<br>M968\n|number= \n|weight={{convert|3.8|kg|lbs}}\n|length={{convert|125|cm|in}}\n|part_length={{convert|74.3|cm|in}}\n|cartridge=[[7\u00d757mm Mauser]]<br>\n|action=[[Bolt-action]]\n|velocity=\n|range=\n|feed=5-round [[stripper clip]], internal [[Magazine (firearm)|magazine]]\n|sights= [[Iron sight]]s adjustable to {{convert|2000|m|yd}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Mauser Model 1908''' were series of [[Gewehr 98]] pattern bolt-action rifles. First produced by [[Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken]] (DWM) and [[Mauser]], they were exported to [[Uruguay]] and [[Brazil]]. In this latter country, [[IMBEL|Itajuba arms factory]] produced upgraded versions until the rifle was replaced by the [[FN FAL]].\n\n== Design ==\n=== Model 1908 ===\nThe Model 1908 rifle was a copy of the Mauser Gewehr 98, chambered in [[7\u00d757mm Mauser]]{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=65}} and with a simple tangent-leaf sight and a longer upper hand-guard.{{sfn|Out|1992|p=17}} A variant was also shortened to a {{convert|1.19|m|in|abbr=on}}-short rifle configuration.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=66}}\n\n=== Models 1935 and 08/34 ===\n[[File:Minist\u00e9rio agracia quase 300 personalidades com Ordem do M\u00e9rito da Defesa (9517559872).jpg|thumb|left|Brazilian soldiers in 2013 with Mauser 1935 or 08/34 short rifles.]]\nThe 7mm Mauser-made Model 1935 rifle was similar to the Model 1908 but featured grasping grooves.{{sfn|Out|1992|p=18}} A short rifle variant also existed.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=70}} Not to be confused with the Czech-made Model 1908/34 police carbine ([[Vz. 33#Vz. 12/33|Vz. 12/33]]), the '''Model 1908/34 short rifle''' was an upgraded version of the Model 1908 using local wood.<ref name=\"armasonline\"/>\n\n=== Later variants ===\nThe '''Mosquet\u00e3o Itajub\u00e1 M1949''' was a 08/34 short rifle chambered in [[.30-06 Springfield]]. The '''Mosquet\u00e3o Itajub\u00e1 M954'''<ref name=\"armasonline\">{{cite web|title=Fuz\u00eds Mauser no Brasil e as Espingardas da F\u00e1brica de Itajub\u00e1 (Rev. 2)|url=https://armasonline.org/armas-on-line/as-espingardas-da-fabrica-de-itajuba/|date=5 April 2011|first=Carlos F. P.|last= Neto|website=armasonline.org|language=pt}}</ref> was a variant fitted with a threaded muzzle, that enabled the use of a [[flash suppressor]] or of a [[rifle grenade|grenade launcher]]. Its buttplate was inspired by the one of the [[Gewehr 43]] (a copy of which was manufactured under the same {{ill|Itajub\u00e1 M954 Mosquet\u00e3o|pt}} designation).{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=73}}\n[[File:Carcar\u00e1 (4968096673).jpg|thumb|left|A Mauser M968 in a ceremony of the [[Military Police (Brazil)|Military Police]] in 2010.]]\nThe '''Mosquet\u00e3o 7,62mm Modelo 968'''<ref name=\"armasonline\"/> or M968 was one of the last Mauser service rifle produced. This rifle fired the [[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]] cartridge, a grenade launcher was fixed to its barrel and its stock was renforced with [[Natural rubber|rubber]]. These features were also used on the FN FAL,{{sfn|Out|1992|p=21}} hence the ''Mosquefal'' nickname.<ref name=\"armasonline\"/>\n\n== History and service ==\nLarge numbers of Model 1908 rifles and short rifles was purchased between 1908 and 1914.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=65}} While DWM was the main manufacturer, Mauser produced 100,000 Model 1908 with ''DWM Obendorf'' stamps.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=235}} Some Mauser 1908 saw combat during the [[Contestado War]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Aureliano|last= Pinto de Moura  |title=Semin\u00e1rio 100 Anos da Guerra do Contestado |date=1 August 2012|language=pt|url=https://www.mpsc.mp.br/noticias/seminario-100-anos-da-guerra-do-contestado|website=mpsc.mp.br|publisher=Minist\u00e9rio P\u00fablico de Santa Catarina}}</ref> Later, Model 1935 rifles and short rifles were purchased in unknown quantities from Mauser.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=69}}{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=70}} They were fielded against the [[Canga\u00e7o]] bandits.<ref name=\"armasonline\"/> To improve the country's independence from foreign suppliers, the Model 08/34 was produced in [[Itajuba]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=70}}\n\nUruguay received DWM-made Model 1908 rifles and short rifles before 1914 and used them into the 1950s.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=391}} Several ''Mystery Mausers'', similar to the Model 1908 but chambered in [[7.92\u00d757mm Mauser]], can be found with Arabic markings or an [[hexagram]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=405}}\n\nIn the early 1950s, surplus Brazilian 1908 rifles and short rifles were exported to the [[Dominican Republic]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=125}} The Brazilian markings were replaced by Dominican markings and the rifles were designated Model 1953.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=126}} During the US intervention in the [[Dominican Civil War]], these Mauser rifles were found to be very effective since they had longer range than the [[M16 rifle]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Power Pack: U.S. Intervention in the Dominican Republic, 1965-1966 |series=Leavenworth Papers, Number 15|last=Yates|first= Lawrence A. |date=July 1988|page= 123|publisher= [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]]|url= https://history.army.mil/html/bookshelves/resmat/dom_republic/Power_Pack-US_Intervention_Dominican_Republic_1965-1966.pdf}}</ref>\n\nPost-war, Itajuba plant produced the M1949 and M954 short rifles for the Brazilian armed forces.{{snf|Ball|2011|p=71}} During the [[Araguaia Guerrilla War]], the rebels were able to acquire 7.62 Mausers from the state police of [[Par\u00e1]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Conflito do Araguaia: Guerrilheiros e Soldados|first=Matias |last=Mendes|url=https://www.gentedeopiniao.com.br/colunista/matias-mendes/conflito-do-araguaia-guerrilheiros-e-soldados|website=Gente de Opini\u00e3o|language=pt|date=24 September 2012}}</ref> The M968 was produced for the Brazilian police.{{sfn|Out|1992|p=21}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ball|first=Robert W. D.|title=Mauser Military Rifles of the World|year=2011|location=Iola|publisher=Gun Digest Books|isbn=9781440228926|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine|title= Les Mauser br\u00e9siliens|first=Roger|last=Out|language=fr|date=December 1992|magazine=[[Gazette des Armes]]|issue=228|pages=17-21|ref=harv}}\n{{Mauser Firearms}}\n\n[[Category:7\u00d757mm Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Rifles of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Weapons and ammunition introduced in 1908]]\n", "name_user": "Le Petit Chat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModels 1935 and 08/34", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mauser_Model_1908"}
{"title_page": "Halestorm", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Alestorm|Hailstorm (disambiguation)}} \n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Halestorm\n| image           = Halestorm - Rock'n'Heim 2015 - 2015235134340 2015-08-23 Rock'n'Heim - Sven - 5DS R - 0049 - 5DSR1815 mod.jpg\n| caption         = Halestorm performing in 2015.\n| image_size      = 250px\n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           =\n| origin          = [[Red Lion, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rock.about.com/od/halestorm/p/Halestorm.htm|title=Halestorm|author=Tim Grierson|work=About.com Entertainment|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/gusto/disc-reviews/discs-halestorm-1032k-willie-nelson-joshua-bell-and-friends-20131024|title=Discs: Halestorm, 1032K, Willie Nelson, Joshua Bell and Friends|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[alternative metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6304503/lindsey-stirling-scores-first-airplay-chart-hit-shatter-me-with|title=Lindsey Stirling|work=Billboard|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{nowrap|[[post-grunge]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/halestorm-mn0000662952/biography|title=Halestorm \u2013 Biography \u2013 AllMusic|author=Marisa Brown|work=AllMusic|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{nowrap|[[alternative rock]]}}<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Roche|url=https://www.axs.com/shinedown-and-halestorm-hammer-jacobs-pavilion-in-cleveland-104964|title=Shinedown and Halestorm hammer Jacobs Pavilion in Cleveland|date=August 18, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| years_active    = 1997\u2013present\n| label           = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| associated_acts = <!--See [[Template:Infobox_musical_artist#associated_acts]] before adding-->\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.halestormrocks.com/}}\n| current_members = \n* [[Lzzy Hale]]\n* Arejay Hale\n* Joe Hottinger\n* Josh Smith\n| past_members    = \n* Leo Nessinger\n* Roger Hale\n}}\n\n'''Halestorm''' is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band from [[Red Lion, Pennsylvania]], consisting of lead vocalist and guitarist [[Lzzy Hale]], her brother drummer and percussionist Arejay Hale, guitarist Joe Hottinger, and bassist Josh Smith.{{r|biosummary}} The group's [[Halestorm (album)|self-titled debut album]] was released on April 28, 2009, through [[Atlantic Records]]. Their second album ''[[The Strange Case Of...]]'' was released on April 10, 2012. Its lead single \"[[Love Bites (So Do I)]]\" from that album won the [[Grammy Award]] for Best Hard Rock/Metal Performance on February 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/news/and-the-grammy-went-to-halestorm|title=And The GRAMMY Went To ... Halestorm - GRAMMY.com|work=The GRAMMYs|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2013/02/halestorm_grammy.html|title=Halestorm conquers big boys of hard rock to win first Grammy Award|work=PennLive.com|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> Their third album, ''[[Into the Wild Life]]'' (2015), peaked at number five on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"top 10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8468690/drake-scorpion-fifth-week-no-1-billboard-200|title=Drake's 'Scorpion' Spends Fifth Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|work=Billboard|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> The band's fourth album, ''[[Vicious (Halestorm album)|Vicious]]'' (2018), debuted at number eight on the chart, becoming their second top 10 record.<ref name=\"top 10\"/> \n\nHalestorm is well known for their near non-stop touring, often performing as many as 250 shows a year.{{r|taft|bnet}} Since 2006 they have toured with many hard rock and heavy metal acts including [[Alice Cooper]], [[Alter Bridge]], [[Chevelle (band)|Chevelle]], [[Seether]], [[Staind]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Trapt]], [[Three Days Grace]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Buckcherry]], [[In This Moment]], [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Shinedown]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Stone Sour]], [[Skillet (band)|Skillet]], [[Hellyeah]], [[Heaven & Hell (band)|Heaven & Hell]], [[Evanescence]], [[The Pretty Reckless]], [[Starset]], [[Sevendust]], [[Dorothy (band)|Dorothy]], [[Lita Ford]], [[Godsmack]], [[Bullet for My Valentine]], [[New Years Day (band)|New Years Day]], and [[Stitched Up Heart]]. Halestorm appeared on the first annual [[Rockstar (drink)|Rockstar Energy Drink]] [[Uproar Festival]],{{r|rockstar}}{{r|rockstarweekly}} and in October 2010 the band traveled to [[Japan]] to participate in the [[Loud Park Festival]].{{r|loudpark}} Halestorm also appeared on the [[2010 in music|2010]] [[Taste of Chaos]] tour.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation (1997\u20132004)===\n\nSiblings Arejay and [[Lzzy Hale|Elizabeth \"Lzzy\" Hale]] have been actively writing and performing original music since 1997 when they were 10 and 13 years old, respectively.<ref name=\"starcourier1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.starcourier.com/article/20130724/NEWS/130729698|title=Halestorm to hit Kewanee Saturday night|date=July 24, 2013|author=Dave Clarke|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Lzzy started learning piano at the age of 5; she later progressed to a [[keytar]], and Arejay the [[drum kit|drums]]. She took guitar lessons at 16. The teen siblings released an [[extended play|EP]] titled ''Don't Mess With the Time Man'' in 1999.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} In 2003, Joe Hottinger joined the band.<ref name=\"starcourier1\"/> In Halestorm's earlier days, Lzzy and Arejay's father, Roger Hale, played bass before Josh Smith joined the group in 2004.<ref name=\"starcourier1\"/>\n\n===''Halestorm'' (2005\u201311)===\nThe group signed a recording contract with [[Atlantic Records]] on June 28, 2005, and released a live EP titled ''[[One and Done]]'' on April 28, 2006. The EP, now out of print, featured an early live version of \"[[It's Not You]].\" Their [[Halestorm (album)|self-titled debut album]] was released on April 28, 2009. The song \"[[I Get Off]]\" served as the album's [[lead single]]. Both the song and video for their second single, \"It's Not You\", were released in late November 2009. Singles and videos for \"Love/Hate Heartbreak\" and \"Familiar Taste of Poison\" were released in 2010.{{r|erg}}\n\nOn November 16, 2010 Halestorm released a live CD/DVD entitled ''[[Live in Philly 2010]]'', which was recorded at [[Theatre of Living Arts|The TLA]] in Philadelphia in early 2010.{{r|live}} On March 22, 2011, Halestorm released an EP called ''[[Reanimate: The Covers EP|ReAnimate]]'' containing [[Cover version|covers]] of songs of different genre.\n\n===''The Strange Case Of...'' (2012\u201313)===\nOn January 24, 2012, Halestorm released the EP ''Hello, It's Mz. Hyde''. Their second full-length album, ''[[The Strange Case Of...]]'' was released on April 10, 2012, in the US,{{r|revolvermag}} April 9 in the UK, and April 17 in [[Italy]]. On October 29, 2012 they were announced as the support for [[Bullet for My Valentine]] on their UK tour in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/halestorm-lzzy-hale-signature-gibson-guitar-via-twitter/|title=Loudwire, May 11, 2012|work=Loudwire|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2012 during a show at the Majestic Theater in [[Madison, Wisconsin]], before Lzzy could start her piano ballad \"Break In\", guitarist Joe Hottinger ran up to her from off stage and told her that the song \"Love Bites...(So Do I)\" was nominated for a Grammy in the [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock/Metal Performance|Best Hard Rock/Metal Performance Category]]. Drummer Arejay Hale asked on his mic what happened and after Lzzy replied to the audience that they had just been nominated for a Grammy,<ref>{{cite web|title=Halestorm|website=Grammy.com|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/halestorm}}</ref> the crowd erupted in celebration. The entire event was recorded by a fan and posted on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Or-lMf9f7gY|title=Lzzy Hale's reaction to her Grammy nomination|date=December 6, 2012}}</ref> On February 10, 2013 Halestorm [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|won the award]], becoming the first female-fronted band to both be nominated and win in that category.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/halestorm|title=Halestorm|date=2014-03-17|website=Grammy.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref> In April 2013, Halestorm reached the top of the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart for the first time with their single \"Freak Like Me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/halestorm/chart-history/mainstream-rock-tracks|title=Halestorm|work=Billboard}}</ref> On August 6, 2013, the band premiered their video for \"Here's To Us\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upvenue.com/article/1770-halestorm-premiere-here-s-to-us-video.html|title=Halestorm Premiere Here's To Us Video|work=UpVenue|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> On October 15, Halestorm released their second covers album entitled ''[[Reanimate 2.0: The Covers EP|Reanimate 2.0]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/halestorm-covers-judas-priest-acdc-marilyn-manson-on-reanimate-2-0-the-covers-ep/|title=Halestorm Covers Judas Priest, AC/DC, Marilyn Manson On 'Reanimate 2.0: The Covers EP'|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]| publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=May 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Into the Wild Life'' (2014\u201318)===\n[[File:Halestorm 2014.jpg|thumb|Halestorm performing in 2014]]\nHalestorm covered the [[Dio (band)|Dio]] song \"Straight Through the Heart\" on the tribute album ''[[Ronnie James Dio \u2013 This Is Your Life]]'', which was released on March 25, 2014. On March 28, 2014 Halestorm performed a brand new song called ''The Heartbreaker'' at the Cannery Ballroom in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} In April, the band released a video on YouTube called ''A Day In The Life Of Halestorm 2014 (Backstage, Interview & New Song ''Mayhem'')''.<ref>{{YouTube|id=jAH3Q4FZZhk|title=HALESTORM \u2013 A day in the life of Halestorm 2014 (backstage, interview & new song \"Mayhem\")}}</ref> The title of the new album was originally set to be released January 13, 2015, but was actually moved a day earlier to January 12.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} The band has posted letters of the album name allowing for fans to try and unscramble them, and on January 12, 2015, their third full studio album entitled ''[[Into the Wild Life]]'' was announced with release dates for the UK and US, April 13 and 14 respectively.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\nIn May, 2015 will be released the photo book ''To Hale And Back'' in collaboration with photographer Rob Fenn, which documents the career of Halestorm so far.<ref>{{cite web|title=Halestorm will release the photo book 'To Hale And Back'|url=http://www.metalrocknews.com/2015/03/halestorm-will-release-photo-book-to.html}}</ref> On January 6, 2017, Halestorm released their third covers album ''[[Reanimate 3.0: The Covers EP|Reanimate 3.0]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/listen-to-halestorm-cover-metallica-soundgarden-classics-on-reanimate-3-0-ep/|title=Listen To HALESTORM Cover METALLICA, SOUNDGARDEN Classics On 'ReAniMate 3.0' EP|date=6 January 2017|work=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref> On May 17, 2017, they released the official music video for the song \"Dear Daughter\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/halestorm-dear-daughter-video/|title=Halestorm Release Emotional Video for 'Dear Daughter'|author=|date=|website=Loudwire|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Vicious'' (2018\u2013present) ===\nIn February 2018, the band announced that work on their next album had begun.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8099040/halestorm-new-album-interview|title=Halestorm Tease 'Very Rock' New Album, Celebrate Philly's Super Bowl Victory|author=|date=|website=billboard.com|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref> By May of the same year, Halestorm announced the release of their next album, ''[[Vicious (Halestorm album)|Vicious]]'' on July 27, 2018. The band released the first single from the album, \"Uncomfortable\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/halestorm-to-release-vicious-album-in-july-uncomfortable-video-now-available/|title=HALESTORM To Release 'Vicious' Album In July; 'Uncomfortable' Video Now Available|date=2018-05-30|work=BLABBERMOUTH.NET|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en-US}}</ref> that same day. It was followed by \"Black Vultures\" on June 22 and \"Do Not Disturb\" on July 19.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} The album came out on July 27. \n\nIn May 2019, \"Chemicals\" was released as a B-side single.  The song is an \"homage to those we\u2019ve lost and all of us struggling with mental illness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalinjection.net/av/new-music/halestorm-drops-b-side-track-chemicals|title=HALESTORM Drops B-Side Track \"Chemicals\"|date=2019-05-01|website=Metal Injection|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> \n\n==Appearances==\n\n[[File:Halestorm performing live at the Laredo Energy Arena.JPG|thumb|250px|Halestorm on a concert at Carnival of Madness in Laredo, Texas on August 14, 2012.]]\n\nHalestorm was the featured artist on the cover of ''Origivation'' magazine in October 2006 and appeared on the cover of ''Pennsylvania Musician'' magazine three times (August 1999, March 2000, and February 2003). Lzzy Hale appeared on the cover of ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' magazine along with Grace Perry from [[Landmine Marathon]] in their December 2009 edition of the \"Hottest Chicks in Metal.\" Lzzy Hale has also been noted for her use of [[Gibson|Gibson Guitars]].{{r|gibson}} Arejay Hale was featured in the June 2010 issue of ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' magazine.\n\nIn mid 2012, Halestorm made a special requested appearance in an episode of [[Bar Rescue]], titled \"[[List of Bar Rescue episodes#Season 2 .282012.29|Owner Ousted]]\", where they performed at the grand opening of the [[Fairfield, Ohio]] bar America Live (formerly Win, Place or Show).\n\nOn January 29, 2013 Halestorm performed on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. On February 22 Lzzy Hale sang the Guns N' Roses song \"Out Ta Get Me\" at [[Bandit Rock|Bandit Rock Awards]] in [[Stockholm|Stockholm Sweden]], where [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] and his band were headlining.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} Lzzy's vocals are featured in a cover of \"[[Close My Eyes Forever]]\" and on the album of [[David Draiman]]'s new project, [[Device (heavy metal band)|Device]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/device-mw0002494905|title=Device \u2013 Device|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a recent [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0diYOG9gcBU interview], Lzzy Hale revealed that she keeps the [https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/where-does-halestorms-lzzy-hale-keep-her-grammy Grammy] on her mantelpiece next to her other favorite trophy from the Schuylkill County Fair in Pennsylvania when Halestorm won 3rd place in a talent contest in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/where-does-halestorms-lzzy-hale-keep-her-grammy|title=Where Does Lzzy Hale Keep Her GRAMMY?|date=2019-01-22|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n;Current members\n* [[Lzzy Hale]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], [[acoustic guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s, [[piano]] <small>(1997\u2013present)</small>, lead guitar <small>(1997\u20132000)</small>, bass <small>(1997\u20131998)</small>\n* Arejay Hale \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] <small>(1997\u2013present)</small>\n* Joe Hottinger \u2013 [[lead guitar]], acoustic guitar, backing vocals <small>(2003\u2013present)</small>\n* Josh Smith \u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], keyboards, piano, backing vocals <small>(2004\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Past members\n* Leo Nessinger \u2013 lead guitar <small>(2000\u20132003)</small>\n* Roger Hale \u2013 bass <small>(1998\u20132004)</small>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:805 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:80 bottom:100 top:5 right:15\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1997 till:{{#time:m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:1997\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1997\n\nColors =\n  id:Vocals    value:red                 legend:Lead_vocals,_rhythm_guitar,_acoustic_guitar\n  id:Guitar    value:green               legend:Lead_guitar\n  id:Bass      value:blue                legend:Bass\n  id:Keys      value:purple              legend:Keyboards,_piano,_backing_vocals\n  id:Drums     value:orange              legend:Drums,_backing_vocals\n  id:Studio    value:black               legend:Studio_album\n  id:Other     value:gray(0.5)           legend:Other_release\n\nLineData =\n  layer:back\n  color:Studio\n  at:04/28/2009\n  at:04/10/2012\n  at:04/14/2015\n  at:07/27/2018\n\n  color:Other\n  at:01/01/1999\n  at:01/01/2001\n  at:04/25/2006\n  at:11/16/2010\n  at:03/22/2011\n  at:11/06/2012\n  at:10/15/2013\n  at:04/15/2016\n  at:01/06/2017\n  \nBarData =\n  bar:LHale     text:\"Lzzy Hale\"\n  bar:Nessinger text:\"Leo Nessinger\"\n  bar:Hottinger text:\"Joe Hottinger\"\n  bar:RHale     text:\"Roger Hale\"\n  bar:Smith     text:\"Josh Smith\"\n  bar:AHale     text:\"Arejay Hale\"\n\nPlotData=\n  width:11\n  bar:LHale     from:start      till:end        color:Vocals\n  bar:LHale     from:start      till:end 