son.com |accessdate=2010-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327051538/http://www.gibson.com/en%2Dus/Lifestyle/News/lzzy%2Dhale%2D0217/ |archivedate=2010-03-27 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"erg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ergmusic.com/usa/compilation.asp?series=NRT |title=Nu Rock Traxx volume 135 \u2013 ERG Music's DJ CD Compilations |publisher=Ergmusic.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rockstar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockstaruproar.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&id=5&Itemid=56 |title=Rockstar Energy Drink UPROAR Festival \u2013 Bands |publisher=Rockstaruproar.com |accessdate=2010-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524025009/http://www.rockstaruproar.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&id=5&Itemid=56 |archivedate=2010-05-24 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"taft\">{{cite web |url=http://www.taftmidwaydriller.com/entertainment/x968921831/20-questions-with-Joe-Hottinger-of-Halestorm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402092234/http://www.taftmidwaydriller.com/entertainment/x968921831/20-questions-with-Joe-Hottinger-of-Halestorm|archivedate=2012-04-02|title=20 questions with Joe Hottinger of Halestorm |first=Gary |last=Darling |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=October 2, 2016 |publisher=Taft Midway Driller }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bnet\">{{cite web |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_pwwi/is_200904/ai_n31596295/ |title=Halestorm Hits Everywhere This Week |date=April 2009 |accessdate=July 16, 2010 |publisher=[[Marketwire]] }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"loudpark\">{{cite web |language=Japanese |url=http://www.loudpark.com/10/news/index.html#0709 |title=LOUD PARK 10:: OFFICIAL SITE \u2013 NEWS |date=July 9, 2010 |accessdate=July 16, 2010 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"live\">{{cite web|url=http://www.halestormrocks.com/blog/its-coming-halestorm-live-in-philly-2010-cddvd/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311151018/http://www.halestormrocks.com/blog/its-coming-halestorm-live-in-philly-2010-cddvd/ |archivedate=2012-03-11 |title=IT'S COMING! Halestorm to release \"Live in Philly 2010\" CD/DVD in 2011 |publisher=HalestormRocks.com |accessdate=2016-10-02 |date=2010-10-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rockstarweekly\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockstarweekly.com/halestorm-releasing-live-cd-and-dvd-in-november.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205033733/http://www.rockstarweekly.com/halestorm-releasing-live-cd-and-dvd-in-november.html|archivedate=2012-02-05|title=Halestorm Releasing Live CD And DVD In November |accessdate=October 2, 2016 |publisher=The RockStar Group }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"revolvermag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/news/halestorm-announce-new-album-the-strange-case-of%E2%80%A6-and-premiere-video.html |title=Halestorm Announce New Album, \u2018The Strange Case Of\u2026\u2019 and Premiere Music |accessdate=February 9, 2012 | date = 2012-01-24 |publisher=Revolver Magazine }}</ref>\n\n<!--add references above this line-->\n<!--Below are unused, possibly useful references\n<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Brown |first=Marisa |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p425415|pure_url=yes}} |title=((( Halestorm > Overview ))) |publisher=allmusic |date= |accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://rock.about.com/od/reviews/fr/HalestormAlbum |title=Halestorm Album Review - Review of Halestorm Rock Band - About.com |publisher=Rock.about.com |date=2009-04-28 |accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"unrated\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unratedmagazine.com/Articles/Archive/2009/Halestorm_June-2009.cfm |title=There's a Hale storm a commin, to your town! |first=Jackie Lee |last=King |date=June 2009 |accessdate=July 10, 2010 |publisher=[[UnRated Magazine]] }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"mgeek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicgeekmedia.com/?p=112 |title=Lzzy Hale of Halestorm gets Geeky with Matt Collen |date=2009-01-08}}</ref>\nhttp://www.zoiksonline.com/2011/03/halestorm-sets-reanimate-covers-ep.html\n-->}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.halestormrocks.com/}}\n* [http://www.atlanticrecords.com/artists/halestorm Halestorm at Atlantic Records]\n* [http://guitar.com/articles/halestorm-interview-lzzy-hale-talks-guitars-and-childhood-dreams-come-true 2015 Lzzy Hale Interview on Guitar.com]\n{{Halestorm}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1997 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American alternative metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:American post-grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hard rock musical groups from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1997]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Alestorm|Hailstorm (disambiguation)}} \n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Halestorm\n| image           = Halestorm - Rock'n'Heim 2015 - 2015235134340 2015-08-23 Rock'n'Heim - Sven - 5DS R - 0049 - 5DSR1815 mod.jpg\n| caption         = Halestorm performing in 2015.\n| image_size      = 250px\n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           =\n| origin          = [[Red Lion, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rock.about.com/od/halestorm/p/Halestorm.htm|title=Halestorm|author=Tim Grierson|work=About.com Entertainment|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/gusto/disc-reviews/discs-halestorm-1032k-willie-nelson-joshua-bell-and-friends-20131024|title=Discs: Halestorm, 1032K, Willie Nelson, Joshua Bell and Friends|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[alternative metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6304503/lindsey-stirling-scores-first-airplay-chart-hit-shatter-me-with|title=Lindsey Stirling|work=Billboard|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{nowrap|[[post-grunge]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/halestorm-mn0000662952/biography|title=Halestorm \u2013 Biography \u2013 AllMusic|author=Marisa Brown|work=AllMusic|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{nowrap|[[alternative rock]]}}<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Roche|url=https://www.axs.com/shinedown-and-halestorm-hammer-jacobs-pavilion-in-cleveland-104964|title=Shinedown and Halestorm hammer Jacobs Pavilion in Cleveland|date=August 18, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| years_active    = 1997\u2013present\n| label           = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| associated_acts = <!--See [[Template:Infobox_musical_artist#associated_acts]] before adding-->\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.halestormrocks.com/}}\n| current_members = \n* [[Lzzy Hale]]\n* Arejay Hale\n* Joe Hottinger\n* Josh Smith\n| past_members    = \n* Leo Nessinger\n* Roger Hale\n}}\n\n'''Halestorm''' is an American [[Rock music|rock]] band from [[Red Lion, Pennsylvania]], consisting of lead vocalist and guitarist [[Lzzy Hale]], her brother drummer and percussionist Arejay Hale, guitarist Joe Hottinger, and bassist Josh Smith.{{r|biosummary}} The group's [[Halestorm (album)|self-titled debut album]] was released on April 28, 2009, through [[Atlantic Records]]. Their second album ''[[The Strange Case Of...]]'' was released on April 10, 2012. Its lead single \"[[Love Bites (So Do I)]]\" from that album won the [[Grammy Award]] for Best Hard Rock/Metal Performance on February 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/news/and-the-grammy-went-to-halestorm|title=And The GRAMMY Went To ... Halestorm - GRAMMY.com|work=The GRAMMYs|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2013/02/halestorm_grammy.html|title=Halestorm conquers big boys of hard rock to win first Grammy Award|work=PennLive.com|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> Their third album, ''[[Into the Wild Life]]'' (2015), peaked at number five on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"top 10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8468690/drake-scorpion-fifth-week-no-1-billboard-200|title=Drake's 'Scorpion' Spends Fifth Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|work=Billboard|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> The band's fourth album, ''[[Vicious (Halestorm album)|Vicious]]'' (2018), debuted at number eight on the chart, becoming their second top 10 record.<ref name=\"top 10\"/> \n\nHalestorm is well known for their near non-stop touring, often performing as many as 250 shows a year.{{r|taft|bnet}} Since 2006 they have toured with many hard rock and heavy metal acts including [[Alice Cooper]], [[Alter Bridge]], [[Chevelle (band)|Chevelle]], [[Seether]], [[Staind]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Trapt]], [[Three Days Grace]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Buckcherry]], [[In This Moment]], [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Shinedown]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Stone Sour]], [[Skillet (band)|Skillet]], [[Hellyeah]], [[Heaven & Hell (band)|Heaven & Hell]], [[Evanescence]], [[The Pretty Reckless]], [[Starset]], [[Sevendust]], [[Dorothy (band)|Dorothy]], [[Lita Ford]], [[Godsmack]], [[Bullet for My Valentine]], [[New Years Day (band)|New Years Day]], and [[Stitched Up Heart]]. Halestorm appeared on the first annual [[Rockstar (drink)|Rockstar Energy Drink]] [[Uproar Festival]],{{r|rockstar}}{{r|rockstarweekly}} and in October 2010 the band traveled to [[Japan]] to participate in the [[Loud Park Festival]].{{r|loudpark}} Halestorm also appeared on the [[2010 in music|2010]] [[Taste of Chaos]] tour.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation (1997\u20132004)===\n\nSiblings Arejay and [[Lzzy Hale|Elizabeth \"Lzzy\" Hale]] have been actively writing and performing original music since 1997 when they were 10 and 13 years old, respectively.<ref name=\"starcourier1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.starcourier.com/article/20130724/NEWS/130729698|title=Halestorm to hit Kewanee Saturday night|date=July 24, 2013|author=Dave Clarke|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Lzzy started learning piano at the age of 5; she later progressed to a [[keytar]], and Arejay the [[drum kit|drums]]. She took guitar lessons at 16. The teen siblings released an [[extended play|EP]] titled ''Don't Mess With the Time Man'' in 1999.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} In 2003, Joe Hottinger joined the band.<ref name=\"starcourier1\"/> In Halestorm's earlier days, Lzzy and Arejay's father, Roger Hale, played bass before Josh Smith joined the group in 2004.<ref name=\"starcourier1\"/>\n\n===''Halestorm'' (2005\u201311)===\nThe group signed a recording contract with [[Atlantic Records]] on June 28, 2005, and released a live EP titled ''[[One and Done]]'' on April 28, 2006. The EP, now out of print, featured an early live version of \"[[It's Not You]].\" Their [[Halestorm (album)|self-titled debut album]] was released on April 28, 2009. The song \"[[I Get Off]]\" served as the album's [[lead single]]. Both the song and video for their second single, \"It's Not You\", were released in late November 2009. Singles and videos for \"Love/Hate Heartbreak\" and \"Familiar Taste of Poison\" were released in 2010.{{r|erg}}\n\nOn November 16, 2010 Halestorm released a live CD/DVD entitled ''[[Live in Philly 2010]]'', which was recorded at [[Theatre of Living Arts|The TLA]] in Philadelphia in early 2010.{{r|live}} On March 22, 2011, Halestorm released an EP called ''[[Reanimate: The Covers EP|ReAnimate]]'' containing [[Cover version|covers]] of songs of different genre.\n\n===''The Strange Case Of...'' (2012\u201313)===\nOn January 24, 2012, Halestorm released the EP ''Hello, It's Mz. Hyde''. Their second full-length album, ''[[The Strange Case Of...]]'' was released on April 10, 2012, in the US,{{r|revolvermag}} April 9 in the UK, and April 17 in [[Italy]]. On October 29, 2012 they were announced as the support for [[Bullet for My Valentine]] on their UK tour in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/halestorm-lzzy-hale-signature-gibson-guitar-via-twitter/|title=Loudwire, May 11, 2012|work=Loudwire|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2012 during a show at the Majestic Theater in [[Madison, Wisconsin]], before Lzzy could start her piano ballad \"Break In\", guitarist Joe Hottinger ran up to her from off stage and told her that the song \"Love Bites...(So Do I)\" was nominated for a Grammy in the [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock/Metal Performance|Best Hard Rock/Metal Performance Category]]. Drummer Arejay Hale asked on his mic what happened and after Lzzy replied to the audience that they had just been nominated for a Grammy,<ref>{{cite web|title=Halestorm|website=Grammy.com|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/halestorm}}</ref> the crowd erupted in celebration. The entire event was recorded by a fan and posted on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Or-lMf9f7gY|title=Lzzy Hale's reaction to her Grammy nomination|date=December 6, 2012}}</ref> On February 10, 2013 Halestorm [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|won the award]], becoming the first female-fronted band to both be nominated and win in that category.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/halestorm|title=Halestorm|date=2014-03-17|website=Grammy.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref> In April 2013, Halestorm reached the top of the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart for the first time with their single \"Freak Like Me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/halestorm/chart-history/mainstream-rock-tracks|title=Halestorm|work=Billboard}}</ref> On August 6, 2013, the band premiered their video for \"Here's To Us\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upvenue.com/article/1770-halestorm-premiere-here-s-to-us-video.html|title=Halestorm Premiere Here's To Us Video|work=UpVenue|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> On October 15, Halestorm released their second covers album entitled ''[[Reanimate 2.0: The Covers EP|Reanimate 2.0]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/halestorm-covers-judas-priest-acdc-marilyn-manson-on-reanimate-2-0-the-covers-ep/|title=Halestorm Covers Judas Priest, AC/DC, Marilyn Manson On 'Reanimate 2.0: The Covers EP'|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]| publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=May 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Into the Wild Life'' (2014\u201318)===\n[[File:Halestorm 2014.jpg|thumb|Halestorm performing in 2014]]\nHalestorm covered the [[Dio (band)|Dio]] song \"Straight Through the Heart\" on the tribute album ''[[Ronnie James Dio \u2013 This Is Your Life]]'', which was released on March 25, 2014. On March 28, 2014 Halestorm performed a brand new song called ''The Heartbreaker'' at the Cannery Ballroom in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} In April, the band released a video on YouTube called ''A Day In The Life Of Halestorm 2014 (Backstage, Interview & New Song ''Mayhem'')''.<ref>{{YouTube|id=jAH3Q4FZZhk|title=HALESTORM \u2013 A day in the life of Halestorm 2014 (backstage, interview & new song \"Mayhem\")}}</ref> The title of the new album was originally set to be released January 13, 2015, but was actually moved a day earlier to January 12.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} The band has posted letters of the album name allowing for fans to try and unscramble them, and on January 12, 2015, their third full studio album entitled ''[[Into the Wild Life]]'' was announced with release dates for the UK and US, April 13 and 14 respectively.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\nIn May, 2015 will be released the photo book ''To Hale And Back'' in collaboration with photographer Rob Fenn, which documents the career of Halestorm so far.<ref>{{cite web|title=Halestorm will release the photo book 'To Hale And Back'|url=http://www.metalrocknews.com/2015/03/halestorm-will-release-photo-book-to.html}}</ref> On January 6, 2017, Halestorm released their third covers album ''[[Reanimate 3.0: The Covers EP|Reanimate 3.0]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/listen-to-halestorm-cover-metallica-soundgarden-classics-on-reanimate-3-0-ep/|title=Listen To HALESTORM Cover METALLICA, SOUNDGARDEN Classics On 'ReAniMate 3.0' EP|date=6 January 2017|work=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref> On May 17, 2017, they released the official music video for the song \"Dear Daughter\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/halestorm-dear-daughter-video/|title=Halestorm Release Emotional Video for 'Dear Daughter'|author=|date=|website=Loudwire|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Vicious'' (2018\u2013present) ===\nIn February 2018, the band announced that work on their next album had begun.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8099040/halestorm-new-album-interview|title=Halestorm Tease 'Very Rock' New Album, Celebrate Philly's Super Bowl Victory|author=|date=|website=billboard.com|accessdate=1 April 2018}}</ref> By May of the same year, Halestorm announced the release of their next album, ''[[Vicious (Halestorm album)|Vicious]]'' on July 27, 2018. The band released the first single from the album, \"Uncomfortable\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/halestorm-to-release-vicious-album-in-july-uncomfortable-video-now-available/|title=HALESTORM To Release 'Vicious' Album In July; 'Uncomfortable' Video Now Available|date=2018-05-30|work=BLABBERMOUTH.NET|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en-US}}</ref> that same day. It was followed by \"Black Vultures\" on June 22 and \"Do Not Disturb\" on July 19.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} The album came out on July 27. \n\nIn May 2019, \"Chemicals\" was released as a B-side single.  The song is an \"homage to those we\u2019ve lost and all of us struggling with mental illness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalinjection.net/av/new-music/halestorm-drops-b-side-track-chemicals|title=HALESTORM Drops B-Side Track \"Chemicals\"|date=2019-05-01|website=Metal Injection|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> \n\n==Appearances==\n\n[[File:Halestorm performing live at the Laredo Energy Arena.JPG|thumb|250px|Halestorm on a concert at Carnival of Madness in Laredo, Texas on August 14, 2012.]]\n\nHalestorm was the featured artist on the cover of ''Origivation'' magazine in October 2006 and appeared on the cover of ''Pennsylvania Musician'' magazine three times (August 1999, March 2000, and February 2003). Lzzy Hale appeared on the cover of ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' magazine along with Grace Perry from [[Landmine Marathon]] in their December 2009 edition of the \"Hottest Chicks in Metal.\" Lzzy Hale has also been noted for her use of [[Gibson|Gibson Guitars]].{{r|gibson}} Arejay Hale was featured in the June 2010 issue of ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' magazine.\n\nIn mid 2012, Halestorm made a special requested appearance in an episode of [[Bar Rescue]], titled \"[[List of Bar Rescue episodes#Season 2 .282012.29|Owner Ousted]]\", where they performed at the grand opening of the [[Fairfield, Ohio]] bar America Live (formerly Win, Place or Show).\n\nOn January 29, 2013 Halestorm performed on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. On February 22 Lzzy Hale sang the Guns N' Roses song \"Out Ta Get Me\" at [[Bandit Rock|Bandit Rock Awards]] in [[Stockholm|Stockholm Sweden]], where [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] and his band were headlining.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} Lzzy's vocals are featured in a cover of \"[[Close My Eyes Forever]]\" and on the album of [[David Draiman]]'s new project, [[Device (heavy metal band)|Device]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/device-mw0002494905|title=Device \u2013 Device|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a recent [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0diYOG9gcBU interview], Lzzy Hale revealed that she keeps the [https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/where-does-halestorms-lzzy-hale-keep-her-grammy Grammy] on her mantelpiece next to her other favorite trophy from the The Schuylkill County Fair in Pennsylvania when Halestorm won 3rd place in a talent contest in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/where-does-halestorms-lzzy-hale-keep-her-grammy|title=Where Does Lzzy Hale Keep Her GRAMMY?|date=2019-01-22|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n;Current members\n* [[Lzzy Hale]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], [[acoustic guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s, [[piano]] <small>(1997\u2013present)</small>, lead guitar <small>(1997\u20132000)</small>, bass <small>(1997\u20131998)</small>\n* Arejay Hale \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] <small>(1997\u2013present)</small>\n* Joe Hottinger \u2013 [[lead guitar]], acoustic guitar, backing vocals <small>(2003\u2013present)</small>\n* Josh Smith \u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], keyboards, piano, backing vocals <small>(2004\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Past members\n* Leo Nessinger \u2013 lead guitar <small>(2000\u20132003)</small>\n* Roger Hale \u2013 bass <small>(1998\u20132004)</small>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:805 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:80 bottom:100 top:5 right:15\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1997 till:{{#time:m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:1997\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1997\n\nColors =\n  id:Vocals    value:red                 legend:Lead_vocals,_rhythm_guitar,_acoustic_guitar\n  id:Guitar    value:green               legend:Lead_guitar\n  id:Bass      value:blue                legend:Bass\n  id:Keys      value:purple              legend:Keyboards,_piano,_backing_vocals\n  id:Drums     value:orange              lege